[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Hi, I am Grandmaster Fidel Corrales, and welcome to my first Chessable course, Mayhem in the Scotch!  I have had experience with the Scotch for almost 20 years, but I decided to make it my main Opening against 1.e4 e5, almost exclusively, only 10 years ago. The reason, is that the Scotch is much less theoretically loaded than the Spanish or Italian openings, and it gives you the freedom to choose the pawn structure you want to go for.  This is very important for me, as an active player in the US open tournaments circuit, since it allows me to get my opponents into my territory and not vice versa. This is specially important against stronger opponents, which is a plus the Scotch offers.  But more importantly, it is also true for my students. The uneven positions arising from the Scotch level the field when thy face stronger opponents too, but often throw off balance the weaker ones. That makes it a powerful practical opening choice, and none of them have ever dropped the Scotch after learning it!  So, I invite you to join the club! }
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from.With today's deep opening preparation, it's very important to have as many alternative lines in your repertoire as possible, so that it's harder for your opponents to lure you into their opening traps. The more options inside the Scotch, the better it is for you, and that's what I am trying to accomplish throughout this course. }
5. Nxc6
{ 5.Nc3!?  This is the more boring line! It also gives White easy play, but it doesn't really challenge Black. I strongly recommend to study a beautiful game played recently by Hikaru Nakamura, were he beats Fabiano Caruana in beautiful style. However, such games are not typical for this line.  5...Bb4!  The best move. Black puts pressure on e4 by pinning and attacking the Nc3, which forces White's next move.  6.Nxc6  bxc6  7.Bd3⩲  White does not have a big advantage, but a small long-term edge. If you are looking for a likely draw and zero complications, this could be a good line for you. }
5... bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure.   8.c4  Let's see some examples of how delaying this move by beginning with 8.h4 favors White.  8...Nb6   8...Ba6  It is not possible for Black to play this move immediately after 8.h4, so if Black wishes to play any type of ...Ba6, they have to work harder. That's one of the main ideas of starting with 8.h4. You can see that Black needs to wait for c4 to happen or they first have to play ...a5 in order to force the ...Ba6 move.  9.Nc3  This position is a tabiya in the traditional Scotch, which was played successfully by many top players, including Kasparov. With h4 included we gain the extra possibility of g3! followed by Bh3, which eventually wins a tempo if Black puts the queen on e6. We can also route the queenside knight via d2-f3-g5 or d4, to again use the position of Black's queen to our advantage.  9...Ba6   9...d5  This is one of the few lines where starting with 8.c4 over 8.h4 favors White, because in the 8.h4 line we don't have a knight on c3 which helps put pressure on the d5-pawn. This is a trade-off for all the other benefits we will experience with the 8.h4 line.  10.exd6  cxd6  11.Be3⩲  This position is considered good for White, but if you add in the moves h4 and ...a5, White's advantage increases further.   9...d6  leads to the same thing as 9...d5 after  10.exd6  .   9...Qe6  10.Qe4  1-0 @@StartBracket@@36@@EndBracket@@ Kasparov,G @@StartBracket@@2851@@EndBracket@@-Timman,J @@StartBracket@@2655@@EndBracket@@ Wijk aan Zee 2000  10.b3  O-O-O  Now imagine the same position but with h4 and ...a5 included. This inclusion can only benefit White, as ...a5 is not that helpful. In fact, it has weakened Black's king. In the actual theory of 8.h4, White would be able to play 12. Bf4! instead of Bb2, and Black wouldnt be able to play 12...g5 due to the pawn on h4.  11.Bf4  I am just showing this move to make a point.   11.Bb2!  is the best move!  11...Re8  With a complicated position. I played this vs Magnus and lost in the 2021 Blitz World Cup.  11...g5!  Here Black has this move, which is obviously not great if White's pawn was on h4. But without that pawn on h4 the position is clearly better for Black. }
8... Qe6 { After 8...Qe6 I offer two options: } 9. Nd2
{ 9.Nd2  is my main recommendation, considered in chapter 1.   9.g3!  is an alternative, considered in chapter 2.   9.h5!?  is also interesting, and I briefly analyze this move in the 9.Nd2 chapter. }
*

