[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "8...Qe6 9.Nd2 with 9...Nb4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ...f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. Nd2
{ I believe this is the most flexible of all of White's possible moves, more or less a waiting move like h4 or g3. Black doesn't have much to do here, so we wait for Black to define their development. We can play c4 at any moment, but it's better to keep Black from playing ...Ba6 a little longer. Another important detail of  9.Nd2  is that many times we will transpose to  9.g3  lines. ---  9.Nd2  allows one move for Black that 9.g3 doesn't, and that's  9...Nf4  . 9. Nd2 also comes with the possibility of Nf3 to defend the pawn on e5, something that 9.g3 doesn't allow. }
9... Nb4
{ Targeting c2 and making ...Ba6 possible, this move makes sense tactically but it does misplace the knight a bit. Now Black has to worry about the possibility of a3, in which case the knight move will look silly. }
10. Nf3
{ The best move! Most of the time when we are in the middle of the opening, if we can develop and protect at the same time, that means we are on the right track. With Nf3 we open the diagonal of the c1 bishop and put the knight on a good square. We also protect the pawn on e5 and release our queen from that duty. White also threatens the annoying move a3, so Black has no time for anything else. }
10... Ba6
{ If Black plays 9...Nb4, the usual continuation is to play 10...Ba6. } 11. c4
{ Another only move! Nothing keeps things together for White except blocking Black's threat by putting the pawn on c4. Now we arrive at the critical moment of this line. Black has many options that will define this position. It's important to note that White's next move could be a3, potentially winning a clear piece. }
11... d5
{ This move looks nice for Black at first glance, but is actually weak. Black is not backing down on their initiative and quickly targets the c4-pawn. White doesn't have an easy way to defend against all threats, which makes this such an attractive move for Black, especially for somebody who has never studied this line before. }
12. a3
{ This moves simply kills any chance of an initiative that Black was dreaming of. It's a gorgeous move that wastes no time and gets right back at Black. White gives up the c4-pawn for a development advantage and the initiative. }
12... Bxc4
{ Black's knight is otherwise trapped, so this is the only move, making the a6-square available. }
13. Qd1
{ The best square for the queen. This is not the only time we will see the queen going back to its original square. The importance of this move is that it keeps all minor pieces open for development, and it also prepares to possibly reroute the queen to a4 in order to put pressure on Black's knight  @@StartBracket@@which will soon be on a6@@EndBracket@@ and the c6-pawn. }
13... Bxf1
{ Another move that makes sense but is bad. The issue with this move is that instead of weakening our king, it actually makes our monarch run to safety as it's now out of the pin on the e-file. The king can be further improved by playing g3-Kg2 or by simply staying on f1, while the rook can be activated with Rh1-h3. }
14. Kxf1
{ Now our king is better positioned than before. Moves like ...f6 or any possible checks are now either non-existent or simply not good. The only issue we need to solve is how to activate our h1-rook, and as mentioned before there are multiple ways to do so. }
14... Na6
{ Black's knight is finally safe, but at a huge cost. A knight on the edge of the board is technically speaking the worst of the worst. This one is especially bad because there is no easy way to bring this knight closer to the center after our next move. }
15. b4
{ White simply takes care of business. This is a logical move that kills any hopes for Black to bring the knight to c5. Next, the c-file will be used to put pressure on the doubled weak pawns, and on top of that, Black needs to worry about White's potential attack on the kingside and development advantage. This is position is really bad for Black with not much of a fight. }
