1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ...f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. Nd2
{ I believe this is the most flexible of all of White's possible moves, more or less a waiting move like h4 or g3. Black doesn't have much to do here, so we wait for Black to define their development. We can play c4 at any moment, but it's better to keep Black from playing ...Ba6 a little longer. Another important detail of  9.Nd2  is that many times we will transpose to  9.g3  lines. ---  9.Nd2  allows one move for Black that 9.g3 doesn't, and that's  9...Nf4  . 9. Nd2 also comes with the possibility of Nf3 to defend the pawn on e5, something that 9.g3 doesn't allow. }
9... a5
{ Similar to the line @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1pp1ppp/2p1q3/3nP3/7P/8/PPP1QPP1/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.g3  a5  , Black tries to develop the light-squared bishop to a6 with tempo. }
10. Nf3
{ The plan of h4 and Nd2-f3 has been accomplished. White has provoked Black into playing the unnecessary move ...a5 and Black will still have to deal with moving the d5-knight. }
10... Ba6
{ Having played 9...a5, Black must make this move or their play makes no sense. }
11. c4 { White threatens to take on d5, so the knight has to move. } 11... Nb6
{ Attacking c4 and possibly following it up with ...d5 or ...a4. } 12. b3
{ Usually this the best way to protect the c4-pawn. Not only does it defend the pawn, but it also makes the knight on b6 and the bishop on a6 obsolete. The a2-b3-c4 chain is the most classic pawn structure in the Scotch. }
12... Bb4+ 13. Bd2
{ Any other move doesn't make sense. If possible, it's generally best to develop and stop a threat at the same time. Now, White is trying to figure out how to get castled, while Black tries to play ...d5. }
13... Bxd2+
{ This simple move that many people @@StartBracket@@including GMs@@EndBracket@@ will play is an inaccuracy. }
14. Qxd2
{ An easy move! White continues coordinating and is now trying to castle short if possible. White is only two moves away from accomplishing this. }
14... d6
{ The issue with this move is that it doesn't put pressure on c4. This means the black bishop on a6 and the knight on b6 are not getting active anytime soon. }
15. Bd3
{ A beautiful pawn sacrifice for speedy development and the initiative. } 15...
dxe5 { Black has to take the pawn to make sense of the previous move. } 16. O-O
{ GM Sychev won a nice game vs GM Khanin in 2018. White has a clear initiative for the pawn, and now Black is the one struggling to castle. For example,  16...O-O  is answered with  17.Bxh7+!  and White is clearly better. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Sychev,K  @@StartBracket@@2534@@EndBracket@@-Khanin,S @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ Sochi 2018 }
