1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ... f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. g3
{ Another waiting move! This makes sense because of the position of the queen on e6. White's next move will be Bg2, or even better, Bh3! Now Black has multiple interesting replies, but after all of them White will get good fighting chances.   One thing that users might ask is: why am I giving two lines vs @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/7P/8/PPP1QPP1/RNB1KB1R b KQkq h3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe6?  Well, both  9.Nd2  and  9.g3  are playable and very interesting for White, and since 8...Qe6 is the preferred move of the top players, I wanted to provide as many possible options for us to fight against such a tough move. The more surprises for our opponent, the more difficult it is for them to prepare against us. I also believe that there are many similaraties and transpositions between both these lines, so it's good for your general knowledge of the 8.h4 variation to study both moves. }
9... d6
{ This is always a very solid approach. Black attempts to trade queens quickly and settle for a slightly inferior endgame. }
10. c4
{ As soon as Black plays ...f6 or ...d6, we play c4! That's part of the idea of the waiting move h4. }
10... Nb6 { Displacing the knight is important. } 11. Bf4
{ 11.Bg2!?  is also interesting for White!  11...dxe5  12.Nd2  Be7  13.O-O  =∞ You can play this way if you are looking for more complications. }
11... dxe5 12. Qxe5
{ The endgame with Black's doubled c-pawns is always good for White. } 12...
Bb4+ 13. Nc3
{ There is not much choice for Black, if they don't exchange queens then we will. }
13... Qxe5+
{ After  13...O-O ?!  14.Qxe6  Bxe6  the bishop is kind of misplaced on e6 because Black would like to make use of the open e-file with a rook.  15.O-O-O  ⩲ gives White a pleasant advantage. }
14. Bxe5 O-O { Black threatens ...Re8, which would pin the bishop. } 15. a3
{ Determining what Black will do with their active bishop as soon as possible.  15.O-O-O  is also possible, with good chances. }
