1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... a5
{ One of those moves that prove that 8.h4 is a good waiting move. Now we have to play  9.c4  in order to take advantage of Black's move! }
9. c4 Ba6 10. g3
{ With Black's pawn on a5, Rh3 ideas are out of the question since Ra3 is no longer a real threat to Black's a6-bishop. Therefore we move on to developing the f1-bishop to g2 or h3.   10.Nd2!?  , as played by Nepo, is also good! This move is similar to many move orders we see in these lines. Many times you can transpose by changing the move order of g3-Nd2-b3 and so on. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@-Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2020 }
10... Nb6 11. b3
{ Now  11...a4  doesn't make sense, because even after the exchange on b3 there is nothing to do on the a-file. In fact, White is the one who will benefit from the opening of that file.   11.Nd2!?  ⩲ Again, this is another possible move order with a good game. }
11... O-O-O
{ Black is now ready to play ...d5!   11...d5  12.exd6!  ⩲  Without going too deep into this position, the endgame will be good for White as one of Black's c- and d-pawns will be weak no matter how Black recaptures. }
12. Bh3 { Using the power of h4 to develop the bishop actively. } 12... f6 13.
e6
{ A typical pawn sacrifice in the Scotch, although we are not technically giving up the pawn this time. White wants to keep the center closed and avoid the queen trade, both of which we achieve with this move, as Black can only recapture on e6 with the pawn. This means that this move gives White more time to castle and finish coordinating, which will help creating an initiative.Now, if Black takes on e6, the c6-pawn will become a new target for our light-squared bishop via the h1-a8 diagonal. Furthermore, even if we do end up losing the e6-pawn, it doesn't matter because we are playing a position with opposite side castling in which Black’s minor pieces are far from being active.   For all of those reasons, if Black plays 13…  dxe6  , then after  14.O-O!  White is clearly better thanks to the future attack on the black king! }
