1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Ba6 { By far the best move, and the only one played by top players. } 10.
Rh3 O-O-O 11. Ra3
{ This move is mainly useful when Black has already castled long. You will notice that this is the case anytime in this course that Black has castled and we have the move Ra3 available. }
11... Nb4
{ The only move. Otherwise we just sacrifice on a6 followed by cxd5. } 12. Ra4
{ Threatening a3, which would win the bishop on a6. } 12... Qxe5
{ The only move that can fight for equality! } 13. Qxe5 fxe5 14. Bg5
{ The idea is to chase Black's rook from the d-file before Black can play ...d5. }
14... Nc2+ { There is nothing else for Black. } 15. Kd1
{ The best move! White needs to be able to develop the knight via d2 to avoid losing any time in the future with Black playing d5-d4. Also, putting the king on d2 would give Black an extra check on b4 later. }
15... Nxa1 16. Bxd8 Kxd8 { The only move, otherwise Black loses the game. } 17.
Rxa6
{ By force we've reached an endgame where Black has to play extremely accurate in order to survive. The knight is trapped on a1 and one small mistake could be the end of the game. We'll discuss this endgame in more detail in the theory section. }
*

