1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Ba6 { By far the best move, and the only one played by top players. } 10.
Rh3 fxe5 11. Bg5
{ This move shows one of the many advantages of h4! It defends the Bg5 if needed, like in this case. }
11... Nf6 { The only decent move to get a good fight. } 12. Re3
{ The classic waiting move of this line. We keep open the possibility of putting the rook on a3 in case Black castles long. }
12... O-O-O 13. Ra3
{ It's now time to bring the rook to the a-file. With the black King on the queenside, this rook is defintely on the right square. we also attack a6 and a7, already creating visible issues in Black's position. }
13... Bb7 { Practically the only move! } 14. Nc3
{ 14.Nd2!?  is another possible move that hasn't been played so far. It's very logical. White tries to castle long and play for an easy attack. }
14... d5
{ A logical move that tries to use Black's extra pawn in the center to fight for space, but it comes with big issues. One of them is the opening of the c-file. }
15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rb3
{ Here we go again with this move! There are a lot of tactical ideas that are based on the rook being on the b-file. This is especially true because of the position of the bishop on b7 and the possibility of Black's king going to b8.Now Black has many possible moves, but they all give up something. White's initiative will become more clear as you go through the analysis. }
16... c6 17. Rc1
{ Control of the c-file and the activity of the rook is currently more important than castling. The white king is perfectly safe in the center. Now White has ideas like Nb5 or Na4-c5. The rook also targets c6 and the king on c8. }
17... Kb8
{ The best move, and an easy one to make because it looks scary to stay on c8 with White's rook being on c1. }
18. Na4
{ All the white pieces are working together for the initiative. The Knight is threatening to come to c5 with a winning attack, and Black needs to defend against this immediately. }
18... Qc7
{ Defending against Nc5 followed by disaster on b7 by opening the f8-bishop's diagonal. }
19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. Rxc5
{ It's clear who has the initiative if you look at White's pieces and compare them to Black's. The worst of all is the bishop on b7, but also both of Black's rooks are not active and don't have much of a future either.   An example of a move that attempts to simplify is  20...h6  . Now White has a quick way of punishing this move.  21.Bxf6!  gxf6  22.Qa6!  White threatens to take on c6 and finish the game.  22...Ka8  The only move to survive.  23.Qa4!!  ±  Followed by Ba6 or Ra3. It's going to be very sad for Black. }
