1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... d6
{ This is a very solid line. Black wants to trade queens and get into an endgame. The Scotch endgames are usually very good for White, though. The exchanges in the center will usually leave Black with some pawn weaknesses. }
9. c4
{ Once again, as soon as Black defines the way they are playing the position, we play c4 to misplace their knight. }
9... Nb6 10. exd6 cxd6
{ Black needs to wait for White to trade queens on e7 if possible. The only issue is that now White has the extra option of avoiding the queen trade. }
11. Be3
{ Keeping the queens on the board and developing. Now White intends to play Nd2 follow by O-O-O or g3, Bg2 and O-O. In both cases Black needs to do something about the queen on e7, which hampers their own development.   11.Nc3!?  is also strong. The idea is to get the better endgame again. We are not worried about Black taking on e2, as we'd develop our f1-bishop to e2 for free. The main point here is that you can play in both ways, with or without the queens, and either way White will get good fighting chances. }
11... Be6 12. Qc2
{ Coordinating and protecting the c4-pawn.  12.Nd2!?  is another good move to continue coordinating. Now the f1-bishop could be developed to g2, after which we would castle long. }
12... Qc7
{ Trying to coordinate makes sense for Black. Long castling looks too dangerous, so Black tries to go short. }
13. Nd2 { Let's not forget about our development. } 13... d5
{ Black needs to get this break in before White castles. } 14. c5
{ Not the only move, but a space gaining one. White will follow up with Bd4 and the white bishop will be very actively placed there, targeting the g7-pawn. Castling either way is good for White. }
