1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... h6
{ This move is not very logical because it justifies the h4 move immediately. This is because we can just play as in the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.c4  line, but with the moves h4 and ...h6 included, which can only benefit White. Many times in the  8.c4  complex Black plays moves like ...g6 or ...g5, the latter of which isn't possible any longer. Also, now we have the chance to play Rh3 in some lines, which is normally not possible after  8.c4  . The only good thing about ...h6 from Black's perspective is that it stops a possible h5-h6 from White, as well as Bg5 ideas. }
9. c4 Ba6
{ This move provides an extra justification for White's 8.h4, so it doesn't help Black at all. }
10. Rh3
{ Not the only good move,  10.b3  and  10.Qe4  are also both great moves. However, with  10.Rh3  we take advantage of having played h4 and Black having played ...Ba6 early. }
10... Nb6 11. Nd2
{ Other moves like  11.b3  are also good, but we want to leave the third rank open for the rook in case we want to play Ra3. While we keep the option open for a potential Ra3, we develop an important piece and give Black the chance to let us know how they are intending to develop. This move is always the most flexible one of all! }
11... g6
{ Black understands that castling long is very dangerous, so they try to go short instead. This move has a problem of its own: it weakens the f6-square, and we are ready to exploit that with our knight.   11...O-O-O ?!  As we'll see in many variations in this course, the moment Black plays ...O-O-O, we instantly swing the rook over!  12.Ra3!!  ±  Our waiting has worked! The rook is in the best possible place! }
12. Ra3 { Chasing Black's bishop away so it doesn't pressure c4 any longer. }
12... Bb7 13. Ne4 { The incoming Nf6 is difficult for Black to deal with. } *

