1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... g6 { Not a move we are expecting to see after 8.h4. } 9. c4 Ba6
{ This is another position that White would have never gotten in the 8.c4 line. Normally, you would play this position without the moves h4 and ...g6 included. This benefits White, as you will see later. }
10. Rh3
{ Again the threat is Ra3! This is an idea that we've seen many times throughout the course. The Rh3 move is a direct response to Black playing ...Ba6. }
10... Bg7
{ Not paying attention to your opponent's threats is not a good way to play chess. }
11. Ra3 Nb4
{ Even though many of you will likely never encounter this position, the tactical ideas of it can be used in many different lines in the 8.h4 variation. With that said, it's important to understand the reasoning behind each move. }
12. Ra4 { White threatens a3, winning a piece. } 12... Bxe5
{ Taking this pawn is bad. Again, it feels wrong to ignore all of White's threats. Black does have a trick in mind, though. }
13. Kd1
{ A gorgeous prophylactic move while the position is on fire! White stops all the tricks on the e-file and is now threatening to play a3 again. White also threatens 14.Rxb4! when the bishop is hanging on e5.   13.a3??  Bxc4!  is the beautiful trap Black was playing for! It removes our queen from the protection of our king, leading to a completely winning position for Black.  14.Qxc4??  I'm giving this line just to show the astonishing mate that follows, but yes White could have avoided this mate by giving up the queen.  14...Bc3+!!  A discovered double check!  15.Kd1  Qe1# }
13... O-O { 13...Bb7  14.Rxb4+- } 14. f4
{ A smart move. White tries to force the trade of queens, after which we'll play a3. With the queens off the board Black won't have any initiative to compensate for the material deficit at all. }
14... Qd6+ 15. Qd2
{ You can run but you cannot escape! Now the queen trade is finally accomplished. The game is practically over for Black. }
15... Bxf4 16. Qxd6 Bxd6 17. a3
{ Well, it took a lot of preparation and tactical ideas to get a3 on the board successfully, but it was worth it. White will win a piece, and even though Black has some pawns to compensate, they are all separated from each other and one of them is doubled. }
