[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ This is by far the most testing and interesting line Black can try against the Scotch, as it requires White to quickly define the course of play. There are only two good ways for White to continue, and those are  5.Nxc6  @@StartBracket@@The move I recommend in this course@@EndBracket@@ and  5.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@The more simple reply@@EndBracket@@. With this course, I wanted to target the more complex line  5.Nxc6!  because it's way more difficult for Black to combat, and it gives White plenty of interesting options to choose from. }
5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7
{ 6...Nd5  is a rare move that has been played a few times by super GMs. It's definitely an inaccuracy. The obvious problem here is that now White has an easier time developing because we don't have a queen sitting on e2, so now after  7.c4!  we get the pawn structure advantage of the Scotch without having to struggle to coordinate our pieces. }
7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4
{ The most exciting line nowadays, and also a waiting move! To better understand the advantage of  8.h4  , it is recommended to study the positions that arise after  8.c4  . One of the general ideas of  8.h4  is to obtain versions of  8.c4  where White has more options, which we can only get on the board by starting with  8.h4  . Typical moves/ideas that we will see in this course are Rh3, Bg5 and g3 followed by Bh3 or h5. These ideas are all dependent on how Black chooses to define their pawn structure. }
8... Bb7
{ This was played by Magnus Carlsen and it's a logical move. Black doesn't want to waste time trying for ...Ba6 anymore. This move will be follow by O-O-O and either ...f6 or ...d6, putting pressure on the e5-pawn. }
9. c4
{ Now that Black isn't going to play ...Ba6 anymore, let's carry out c4 right away. }
9... Nb6 10. Nc3 O-O-O 11. Bf4
{ Protecting the e5-pawn and getting ready to castle long. Another advantage of having the pawn on h4 here is that it doesn't allow Black to play 11...g5.   11.Bg5!?  was played by Magnus online, but it's not as good. }
11... d5 12. exd6
{ Always take on d6 in the Scotch - very rarely we will ignore the en passant. It's important to get rid of our weak pawn on e5 while creating a weak pawn for Black on d6 in its stead. }
12... Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 Bxd6
{ This is the point of taking on e2 first, Black wants to develop the bishop by taking on d6. Otherwise the bishop would be slow to develop from f8. }
14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. O-O-O
{ We reach a typical Scotch endgame where Black is going to suffer for a long time. As you can see, the pawn on d6 is a weakness, and it will remain weak for the entirety of the game. Black cannot alter the pawn structure in a way that helps them get rid of the the weakness of either their c- or d-pawn. }
