[Black "4...Bc5 with 5...Bb4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb4+
{ This is a good alternative to  5...Bb6  for Black. They intend to stop us from being able to develop the b1-knight to c3. This is an unusual line that's been played by some of the best players in the world, so it's worth studying in some depth. }
6. c3
{ This is my favorite reply. Yes, we are blocking the c3-square for our knight, but Black's bishop has to retreat to a passive square in exchange. }
6... Be7
{ An obvious downside to the 5...Bb4+ move for Black is the placement of the Bishop on e7, where it is not as active as it would have been on b6. }
7. f4
{ There is no time to waste! Let's grab space and exploit the fact that the black bishop is not on b6 anymore. This move also gives us the possibility of playing e5, and this could be very annoying for the knight on g8.Another idea is to prepare for ...d5 by being able to play e5. The f4-pawn protects our e-pawn in case of a future e5, so now Black will struggle to get the freeing move ...d5 played.   7.Bd3?  would be a classic mistake, giving away any hope for an opening advantage.  7...d5!  This is why! Allowing ...d5 is no good and so Black equalizes on the spot. }
7... d6
{ This is necessary to prevent us from playing e5, kicking Black's knight once it comes to f6. Without this move there would be no easy way for Black to develop. }
8. Bd3
{ Since Black has played ...d6 we don't care about ...d5 anymore. The bishop is placed perfectly on d3, pointing at h7 and protecting the e4-pawn. If Black plays ...d5 now or in the immediate future, we should immediately answer e5. }
8... Nf6
{ Natural development makes sense. Black wants to follow up with castling and ...Re8. Black's light-squared bishop is also not a good piece. In the future, if ... Bg4 we can play h3 and Black needs to either retreat the bishop or trade it for a knight on f3. }
9. N1d2
{ The knight is making its way to f3, where it will be positioned perfectly. There is no better square for that knight right now. The b3-knight, on the other hand, takes care of c5 and is already developed. }
9... O-O 10. O-O
{ Now Black is in a pickle. There is no easy way to continue developing as ...Bg4 could be answered by Qc2 followed by h3, when the bishop must go back. Since we have put our c-pawn on c3, we take advantage of the b1-h7 diagonal by creating a battery with our queen and bishop. Meanwhile, our d2-knight is en route to f3, where it will be placed perfectly to help push e5 when necessary. }
10... Re8
{ A somewhat natural move. Black tries to play ...Bf8 to control the e5 push and also to put some pressure on e4. Another long-term idea for Black is to place the bishop on g7. It's not the only move, but a logical one and it has been played by Artemiev. }
11. Nf3
{ The knight finishes its development and now White is one step closer to full coordination. White has managed to keep their space advantage and can easily follow up with moves like Qc2-Bd2 and Rae1 with a great position. }
11... Bf8
{ Black targets the pawn on e4 and is ready to play g6-Bg7 to improve the bishop a little bit. }
12. e5
{ Up until this point we've followed Giri's game against Artemiev to the letter, and here I improved on his play in a game of my own. I knew that Giri's  12.Qc2  was the easiest way to protect the pawn and continue developing. However, I had analyzed this position beforehand and during my game against Nguyen I remembered my analysis, so I played the beautiful  12.e5!  instead.White has a big advantage and there is no time to waste to get into action. It feels good when an opponent plays into a line you've prepared beforehand!   12.Qc2!?  as mentioned is natural and very strong! 0-1 @@StartBracket@@44@@EndBracket@@ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ -Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2708@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020 }
12... dxe5 13. fxe5 Nxe5 { This move loses right away to an easy tactic. } 14.
Nxe5 { Now Black cannot retake on e5 because it will lose the queen. } 14...
Rxe5 15. Bxh7+ *

