[Black "4...Bb4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3
{ Black's idea is to lure our pawn to c3 so that we can't directly put a knight on c3 anymore. Now, if White wishes to play Nc3, we need to play c4 first. }
5... Bc5 6. Be3 Bb6 7. Nf5
{ The easiest way to play!  7.Qg4  was played by Kasparov and is also interesting, but I like  7.Nf5  better. }
7... g6 8. Bxb6 axb6
{ Opening the a-file, which gives Black some counterplay. } 9. Ne3
{ This is the main point of Nf5. The knight is now placed on its best possible square, controlling f5 and d5. It will be very difficult for Black to achieve any counterplay in the center. }
9... Nf6 10. f3
{ Intending to build a Maroczy bind position. The next move is c4, and then we will play Nc3. As usual in the Scotch, we are fighting to stop the equalizing move ...d5! }
10... O-O 11. c4 d5
{ A very interesting pawn sacrifice that will be followed by a knight sac. In this very complicated position White must know the theory very well, but if you do, White's advantage is clear. }
12. cxd5 Nxe4
{ The only way to continue as Black. Any other move is too slow - White would just keep the extra pawn as well as the superior central control. }
13. fxe4
{ We have to take the knight. It's the only good answer, trying to keep our material advantage. }
13... Qh4+ 14. Kd2
{ The best move, and the only good move as well!  14.Ke2  would block our development and would make things harder for White. }
14... Qxe4 15. Bd3
{ A developing move that gains a tempo on Black's queen - this has to be the best move.   15.dxc6??  is a huge blunder. White loses the queen after  15...Rd8+!  -+ }
15... Qd4 16. Qb3
{ Here  16.dxc6  is also a mistake. It would allow Black to get back into the game after  16...Qxb2+!!  ∞ }
16... Re8 { Black attacks the e3-knight. White has only one good reply. } 17.
Re1
{ The only way to protect the knight on e3 as the bishop on d3 is pinned. Now White is finally threatening to take on c6, so Black must move the knight. }
17... Ne5
{ Usually when your king is in the center of the board and in trouble, all it takes to defend is to finish your development after which you can hide the king on a safe square. The knight on b1 is a piece that needs to get out and play, so the next move makes a lot of sense. }
18. Na3
{ Now this position is still very tricky, but there is no doubt that Black is slowly running out of tricks. The sooner White coordinates, the more clear it will become. We just need to keep our eyes open for cheap tricks and make sure we do not blunder. }
