1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ...f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. Nd2
{ I believe this is the most flexible of all of White's possible moves, more or less a waiting move like h4 or g3. Black doesn't have much to do here, so we wait for Black to define their development. We can play c4 at any moment, but it's better to keep Black from playing ...Ba6 a little longer. Another important detail of  9.Nd2  is that many times we will transpose to  9.g3  lines. ---  9.Nd2  allows one move for Black that 9.g3 doesn't, and that's  9...Nf4  . 9. Nd2 also comes with the possibility of Nf3 to defend the pawn on e5, something that 9.g3 doesn't allow. }
9... Nf4
{ Black is going for a quick repetition after  10.Qe3  Nd5  11.Qe2  Nf4  etc., but White wants more of course. Overall this move is not very logical, since Black is violating one of the basic principles of opening play: don't move a piece multiple times while other pieces remain undeveloped. }
10. Qe4
{ There is no time to waste. We attack the knight and get ready to develop the f1-bishop. }
10... Ng6
{ Black attacks e5 and also they might play ...d5 next. The good news for White is that in case of ...d5 we are still able to exchange on d6 because our queen on e4 is protected by the knight on d2. }
11. f4
{ The best move! White builds a strong presence in the center, which will make Black pieces look silly. Adding some protection to the pawn on e5 is never a waste in the Scotch. White is now ready to play h5, in which case the g6-knight will have to retreat to a really bad square. }
11... d5
{ This move is almost forced, it's now or never for Black. They have to fight for the center before White's space advantage and initiative increase even further. }
12. Qa4
{ A unique case in the Scotch, as most of the time we will be happy to take on d6 after this break. However, here we put more pressure on Black by keeping the structure as it is. Also, we can afford to make this move because e5 is well protected by the f4-pawn. }
12... Bd7
{ A logical move to get out of of the annoying pin created by White's last move, but this is not the best move for Black. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@93@@EndBracket@@ Dominguez Perez,L @@StartBracket@@2739@@EndBracket@@-Topalov,V @@StartBracket@@2740@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019.   12...h5  would have been better to stop White's h5. After  13.Nf3⩲  White keeps a pleasant advantage. }
13. h5
{ White executes the idea of misplacing Black's knight, with a great game ahead! }
