1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ...f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. Nd2
{ I believe this is the most flexible of all of White's possible moves, more or less a waiting move like h4 or g3. Black doesn't have much to do here, so we wait for Black to define their development. We can play c4 at any moment, but it's better to keep Black from playing ...Ba6 a little longer. Another important detail of  9.Nd2  is that many times we will transpose to  9.g3  lines. ---  9.Nd2  allows one move for Black that 9.g3 doesn't, and that's  9...Nf4  . 9. Nd2 also comes with the possibility of Nf3 to defend the pawn on e5, something that 9.g3 doesn't allow. }
9... Nb4
{ Targeting c2 and making ...Ba6 possible, this move makes sense tactically but it does misplace the knight a bit. Now Black has to worry about the possibility of a3, in which case the knight move will look silly. }
10. Nf3
{ The best move! Most of the time when we are in the middle of the opening, if we can develop and protect at the same time, that means we are on the right track. With Nf3 we open the diagonal of the c1 bishop and put the knight on a good square. We also protect the pawn on e5 and release our queen from that duty. White also threatens the annoying move a3, so Black has no time for anything else. }
10... Ba6
{ If Black plays 9...Nb4, the usual continuation is to play 10...Ba6. } 11. c4
{ Another only move! Nothing keeps things together for White except blocking Black's threat by putting the pawn on c4. Now we arrive at the critical moment of this line. Black has many options that will define this position. It's important to note that White's next move could be a3, potentially winning a clear piece. }
11... Bxc4
{ A blunder! Things will get bad very quickly for Black after a forced continuation. }
12. Qxc4 { The only move. } 12... Qxc4
{ This was Black's idea. By exchanging queens the c2-square becomes unprotected. }
13. Bxc4 Nc2+
{ Black will win our rook, but unfortunately the a1-knight becomes trapped. The worst part is that is not possible for the knight to sacrifice itself for anything. }
14. Kd2
{ On its way to c3, making coordination the easiest for white. We need to make sure the h1-rook can attack the knight on a1 and this is the fastest way to accomplish that. }
14... Nxa1 15. Kc3
{ And there is nothing Black can do stop Be3 and Rxa1. White will be up a bishop and knight for a rook, and will have the initiative as well. White has a completely winning position. }
*

