{ The best move! Most of the time when we are in the middle of the opening, if we can develop and protect at the same time, that means we are on the right track. With Nf3 we open the diagonal of the c1 bishop and put the knight on a good square. We also protect the pawn on e5 and release our queen from that duty. White also threatens the annoying move a3, so Black has no time for anything else. }
10... Ba6
{ If Black plays 9...Nb4, the usual continuation is to play 10...Ba6. } 11. c4
{ Another only move! Nothing keeps things together for White except blocking Black's threat by putting the pawn on c4. Now we arrive at the critical moment of this line. Black has many options that will define this position. It's important to note that White's next move could be a3, potentially winning a clear piece. }
11... Qg6
{ Now White has two good moves, and they are similar in strength and can transpose. I prefer the more aggressive move order, which is  12.h5  . }
12. h5
{ I believe this is the most accurate move for White, as it gives Black no option other than going into an inferior endgame.   12.Nd4!?  is a good try with the idea of stopping Qc2 or Nc2 at once. It's also an attempt to trap Black's queen with 13.h5!  12...c5   12...Bc5  13.Nb3!  A nice tactical move that gives White an important tempo, Black cannot play ...Nc2+ yet, as it will get the knight trapped on a1.  13...Be7  14.h5!  Qc2  The only move to save the queen.   14...Qf5??  15.Nd4+-  15.Nd4!  And this transposes to the line that starts with 12.h5. Please refere to that variation to see the full endgame.  13.h5!  Moving the queen away from any activity.  13...Qb6  14.Nb5→ }
12... Qc2 { The only move! Otherwise Black loses the queen. } 13. Nd4
{ 13.Rh4!?  is a good try that hasn't been played much! The idea is to protect the pawn on c4 so that if  13...Qxe2+  the answer  14.Kxe2  is fine. }
13... Qxe2+ { Another forcing move for Black. } 14. Bxe2
{ White threatens to play the usual a3. Black has an uncomfortable endgame. }
14... c5 15. a3
{ A beautiful resource. White is planning to give up a pawn in exchange for a strong initiative. }
15... cxd4 { Black continues the pattern of playing only moves. } 16. axb4
Bxb4+ 17. Bd2
{ After the bishops are traded, our king is on an active square, ready to attack d4, and we've also coordinated our rooks. As you can see, White's pieces are all active while Black's rooks are not playing at all. }
17... Bxd2+ 18. Kxd2 Bb7 19. Rh4
{ 19.Kd3!?  ⩲ Centralizing the king! This also puts Black in a tough position. If Black plays  19...c5  then  20.b4!  with good play! }
19... c5
{ 19...a5!?  would have given Black more chances, but White is still doing well after  20.Rxd4⩲  . }
20. Ra5
{ And White is already clearly better. He ended up winning a nice endgame in 1-0 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Stevic,H @@StartBracket@@2549@@EndBracket@@-Csonka,B @@StartBracket@@2497@@EndBracket@@ Ajka 2023. }
