1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ...f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. Nd2
{ I believe this is the most flexible of all of White's possible moves, more or less a waiting move like h4 or g3. Black doesn't have much to do here, so we wait for Black to define their development. We can play c4 at any moment, but it's better to keep Black from playing ...Ba6 a little longer. Another important detail of  9.Nd2  is that many times we will transpose to  9.g3  lines. ---  9.Nd2  allows one move for Black that 9.g3 doesn't, and that's  9...Nf4  . 9. Nd2 also comes with the possibility of Nf3 to defend the pawn on e5, something that 9.g3 doesn't allow. }
9... Nb4
{ Targeting c2 and making ...Ba6 possible, this move makes sense tactically but it does misplace the knight a bit. Now Black has to worry about the possibility of a3, in which case the knight move will look silly. }
10. Nf3
{ The best move! Most of the time when we are in the middle of the opening, if we can develop and protect at the same time, that means we are on the right track. With Nf3 we open the diagonal of the c1 bishop and put the knight on a good square. We also protect the pawn on e5 and release our queen from that duty. White also threatens the annoying move a3, so Black has no time for anything else. }
10... Ba6
{ If Black plays 9...Nb4, the usual continuation is to play 10...Ba6. } 11. c4
{ Another only move! Nothing keeps things together for White except blocking Black's threat by putting the pawn on c4. Now we arrive at the critical moment of this line. Black has many options that will define this position. It's important to note that White's next move could be a3, potentially winning a clear piece. }
11... c5
{ One of the two best moves for Black. This gives the knight an escape square on c6 and opens the diagonal a8-h1 for the light-squared bishop. Now White has multiple ways of getting an advantage and they are all equally strong, so it's difficult to make a choice. }
12. Ng5
{ A more aggressive approach, which delays the development of Black's f8-bishop. The black queen is attacked and has to go back to where it came from @@StartBracket@@e7@@EndBracket@@. Any other queen move is followed by either  12...--  13.Qf3  or  13.g4  and then  --  14.Qf3  , instantly winning the game.   12.a3!?  White wants to develop the bishop to d2, and this is not possible as long as Black's knight is on b4, so let's kick it out.  12...Nc6  13.Bd2  White would like to castle long and place the bishop on c3, where it is strongly positioned for a possible ...d6, ...d5 or ...f6 break.  13...Be7  14.Bc3⩲  f6  1-0 @@StartBracket@@53@@EndBracket@@ Vachier Lagrave,M @@StartBracket@@2727@@EndBracket@@-Keymer,V  @@StartBracket@@2717@@EndBracket@@ Kolkata IND 2023 The Week in Chess 1505.  15.exf6  Qxe2+  16.Bxe2  Bxf6  17.Bxf6  gxf6  18.Bd3!  ⩲  Keeping options open for the white king. In some cases the king might be better placed on d2, and that's why Black goes for O-O-O to prepare a quick ...d5 in case of Kd2. }
12... Qe7
{ Black needs to protect f7 to avoid the monster fork with Qf3. Even though this is Black's best move, it's always sad to go back and waste time. }
13. Bf4
{ Again, White is trying to castle long, so there is no need to go about developing the f1 bishop yet. Instead White focuses on developing the queenside.   13.Rh3!?  Not surprisingly, this is a decent move! We use h4 to activate the rook via the 3rd rank. This rook could be used to protect the weak e5-pawn and to play a potential Ra3 or Rb3. }
13... O-O-O 14. a3
{ The simplest approach.   14.Rh3!?  As usual in the h4 line, Rh3 is always available. Many times it is the best move, or simply an interesting idea. }
14... Nc6
{ 1-0 @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Acs,P @@StartBracket@@2572@@EndBracket@@-Van den Doel,E  @@StartBracket@@2582@@EndBracket@@ Belgium 2022 }
15. O-O-O
{ It looks like this move allows the strong ...Nd4, but actually that would be an error for Black. }
15... Nd4 16. Qd3
{ Now the knight is a target on d4, and White can put pressure on it to kick it out of there. The other advantage of this move is that White is not losing time: White was supposed to develop the f1-bishop anyway, and at the same time we are targeting the h7-pawn. }
16... g6
{ Stopping the Nxh7 threat and preparing to develop the bishop to g7.   16...f6  17.Nxh7!  ⩲ }
17. Ne4
{ White has the better pawn structure and is threatening multiple tactics, like  17...--  18.Nxc5!  or  18.Bg5!  . White will keep the pressure and initiative as Black has to struggle to defend against all threats. }
