1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ...f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. Nd2
{ I believe this is the most flexible of all of White's possible moves, more or less a waiting move like h4 or g3. Black doesn't have much to do here, so we wait for Black to define their development. We can play c4 at any moment, but it's better to keep Black from playing ...Ba6 a little longer. Another important detail of  9.Nd2  is that many times we will transpose to  9.g3  lines. ---  9.Nd2  allows one move for Black that 9.g3 doesn't, and that's  9...Nf4  . 9. Nd2 also comes with the possibility of Nf3 to defend the pawn on e5, something that 9.g3 doesn't allow. }
9... a5
{ Similar to the line @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1pp1ppp/2p1q3/3nP3/7P/8/PPP1QPP1/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.g3  a5  , Black tries to develop the light-squared bishop to a6 with tempo. }
10. Nf3
{ The plan of h4 and Nd2-f3 has been accomplished. White has provoked Black into playing the unnecessary move ...a5 and Black will still have to deal with moving the d5-knight.   10.g3!?  is also possible! White can now develop the f1-bishop to h3 with tempo.  10...Nb4   10...Ba6  11.c4  transposes to lines of 9.g3 instead of 9.Nd2. Please refer to the 9.g3 chapter for a deeper understanding of the position.  11.Nf3  Ba6  12.c4  Qg6  13.h5!   @@StartBracket@@  13.Kd1!?  was played in a game between top GMs, with the idea of trapping the queen on g6 and stopping Black's threats on c2. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@68@@EndBracket@@ Aryan, C @@StartBracket@@2634@@EndBracket@@-Bluebaum,M @@StartBracket@@2668@@EndBracket@@ Douglas IOM 2023@@EndBracket@@  13...Qc2  14.Rh4↑  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Cheparinov,I @@StartBracket@@2667@@EndBracket@@-Svane, R @@StartBracket@@2615@@EndBracket@@ Krasnaya Polyana 2021 }
10... Ba6
{ Having played 9...a5, Black must make this move or their play makes no sense. }
11. c4 { White threatens to take on d5, so the knight has to move. } 11... Nb4
{ A mistake no doubt. The black knight is now stuck on b4, so why would you place it there if White has a move like a3 available? Well, the idea is that if White immediately plays  12.a3  , Black has  12...Bxc4!  and gets serious counterplay. There is an easy way to stop the trick, though... }
12. Nd4
{ With this move White defends against the fork on c2 and the tactical threat of ...Bxc4. Now a3 is coming next and there are no more tricks for Black. }
12... Qe7
{ The only move! Black can escape by placing the knight on d5. This is not possible with the queen on e6 because White could then just take cxd5. }
13. Bg5
{ Another tempo move that develops and attacks at the same time. It's amazing how the h4-pawn is helping White so much in this line.   13.a3!?  is also very good for White, but it's not as precise. Black can simply go back with  13...Nd5  . }
13... Qc5 { There is no other way to keep the material balance. } 14. Rd1
{ With this amazing move White protects the knight on d4 and threatens a3 again, trapping the knight. There is no easy way to defend against this threat, and Black is completely lost. }
14... Nxa2 15. e6
{ And Black can resign! If they take on e6, we crash through with a knight sacrifice on the same square. }
