10. Nf3
{ The plan of h4 and Nd2-f3 has been accomplished. White has provoked Black into playing the unnecessary move ...a5 and Black will still have to deal with moving the d5-knight.   10.g3!?  is also possible! White can now develop the f1-bishop to h3 with tempo.  10...Nb4   10...Ba6  11.c4  transposes to lines of 9.g3 instead of 9.Nd2. Please refer to the 9.g3 chapter for a deeper understanding of the position.  11.Nf3  Ba6  12.c4  Qg6  13.h5!   @@StartBracket@@  13.Kd1!?  was played in a game between top GMs, with the idea of trapping the queen on g6 and stopping Black's threats on c2. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@68@@EndBracket@@ Aryan, C @@StartBracket@@2634@@EndBracket@@-Bluebaum,M @@StartBracket@@2668@@EndBracket@@ Douglas IOM 2023@@EndBracket@@  13...Qc2  14.Rh4↑  1/2-1/2 @@StartBracket@@43@@EndBracket@@ Cheparinov,I @@StartBracket@@2667@@EndBracket@@-Svane, R @@StartBracket@@2615@@EndBracket@@ Krasnaya Polyana 2021 }
10... Ba6
{ Having played 9...a5, Black must make this move or their play makes no sense. }
11. c4 { White threatens to take on d5, so the knight has to move. } 11... Nb6
{ Attacking c4 and possibly following it up with ...d5 or ...a4. } 12. b3
{ Usually this the best way to protect the c4-pawn. Not only does it defend the pawn, but it also makes the knight on b6 and the bishop on a6 obsolete. The a2-b3-c4 chain is the most classic pawn structure in the Scotch. }
12... Bb4+ 13. Bd2
{ Any other move doesn't make sense. If possible, it's generally best to develop and stop a threat at the same time. Now, White is trying to figure out how to get castled, while Black tries to play ...d5. }
13... Bxd2+
{ This simple move that many people @@StartBracket@@including GMs@@EndBracket@@ will play is an inaccuracy. }
14. Qxd2
{ An easy move! White continues coordinating and is now trying to castle short if possible. White is only two moves away from accomplishing this. }
14... d6
{ The issue with this move is that it doesn't put pressure on c4. This means the black bishop on a6 and the knight on b6 are not getting active anytime soon. }
15. Bd3
{ A beautiful pawn sacrifice for speedy development and the initiative. } 15...
dxe5 { Black has to take the pawn to make sense of the previous move. } 16. O-O
{ GM Sychev won a nice game vs GM Khanin in 2018. White has a clear initiative for the pawn, and now Black is the one struggling to castle. For example,  16...O-O  is answered with  17.Bxh7+!  and White is clearly better. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Sychev,K  @@StartBracket@@2534@@EndBracket@@-Khanin,S @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ Sochi 2018 }
