1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ... f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. g3
{ Another waiting move! This makes sense because of the position of the queen on e6. White's next move will be Bg2, or even better, Bh3! Now Black has multiple interesting replies, but after all of them White will get good fighting chances.   One thing that users might ask is: why am I giving two lines vs @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/7P/8/PPP1QPP1/RNB1KB1R b KQkq h3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe6?  Well, both  9.Nd2  and  9.g3  are playable and very interesting for White, and since 8...Qe6 is the preferred move of the top players, I wanted to provide as many possible options for us to fight against such a tough move. The more surprises for our opponent, the more difficult it is for them to prepare against us. I also believe that there are many similaraties and transpositions between both these lines, so it's good for your general knowledge of the 8.h4 variation to study both moves. }
9... Bc5
{ I find this move to be the most annoying one, as it develops the bishop and is very logical. I think Black is almost required to play this move after 9.g3 if they wish to fight for equality. }
10. Bh3 { Here we go again, let's exploit the ...Qe6 move! } 10... f5 11. c4
{ We've delayed c4 enough, and now we are ready to chase away Black's knight. }
11... Nb6
{ Black puts pressure on c4, so we need to defend the pawn before we can castle short. }
12. Nd2
{ Developing and defending.  12.b3  is also possible, but that would lead to a different type of game. }
12... O-O
{ At this moment White needs to be concerned about ...Re8 followed by ...d5 or ...d6. This is the way Black puts pressure on the weak pawn on e5. }
13. O-O Re8 { Now we have: } 14. Nb3
{ 14.Qd3!?  It's hard to say which move is better, as it's possible that  14.Qd3  is better in practice than 14.Nb3. The reason I chose 14.Nb3 is because it feels less active for Black and we end up winning a pawn with a little more clarity.  14...Ba6   14...g6?  This simple move is already a mistake:  15.Re1±  15.Bxf5  Qxe5  16.Bxh7+  Kh8  17.Kg2↑  Nxc4!  with some counterplay for Black! }
14... Bf8
{ The best move.  14...Be7  would make no sense after ...Re8. Black should try to keep the pressure on e5. }
15. c5 Nd5 16. Qf3 { Getting out of the pin and attacking Black's pawn on f5. }
16... Qxe5 17. Bxf5
{ White's pieces are a bit more active right now, but Black is only one move away from completing development. }
17... Ba6
{ The most logical move by far. This creates a problem, as now we cannot go  18.Rd1  because of  18...Be2  and Black wins. White, however, has a beautiful desperado move! }
18. Bxd7 Bxf1
{ Black has no other choice. If the rook moves anywhere, White takes on c6 and then on d5. }
19. Bxe8
{ A nice desperado move. Black has nothing other than recapturing on e8. }
19... Rxe8 20. Kxf1
{ White is up a pawn. The position is still unclear, but Black the one who needs to struggle for equality. }
