14... Bd4 15. Rb1 Qxe5 16. Qxe5
{ The best move! I know it seems strange to trade queens after losing a pawn, but the compensation will be very clear. }
16... Bxe5 17. Ba3
{ There is no time to waste, we need to continue attacking. } 17... Bd6 18.
Bxd6 cxd6 19. a4
{ White is down a pawn, but Black has a minor piece problem. The position is very complex and White has more than sufficient compensation. }
19... Rae8
{ A double-edged position followed by a natural move. Black places the rook on an open file and is trying to become active with ...Re2! }
20. a5
{ This is an obvious move after a4. We follow a classically Scotch idea: play to make Black's minor pieces as bad as possible. }
20... Na8
{ This looks like a weird move, but it's okay. The knight will need to come back via c7-e6-c5. This will take a while, but it's a plan!   20...Nc8  21.b4↑  , with b5 coming, also leaves Black under significant pressure. White has more than enough for the pawn. }
21. Rfd1
{ Indirectly targeting the d6 and d7-pawns wih a future discovered attack like Nf3 or Nf1. Without a doubt we have a very complicated position, but I believe White's compensation and ease to play is visible. }
