{ I find this move to be the most annoying one, as it develops the bishop and is very logical. I think Black is almost required to play this move after 9.g3 if they wish to fight for equality. }
10. Bh3 { Here we go again, let's exploit the ...Qe6 move! } 10... f5 11. c4
{ We've delayed c4 enough, and now we are ready to chase away Black's knight. }
11... Nb6
{ Black puts pressure on c4, so we need to defend the pawn before we can castle short. }
12. Nd2
{ Developing and defending.  12.b3  is also possible, but that would lead to a different type of game. }
12... O-O
{ At this moment White needs to be concerned about ...Re8 followed by ...d5 or ...d6. This is the way Black puts pressure on the weak pawn on e5. }
13. O-O Ba6 14. b3
{ The typical answer to ...Ba6, something we will see many times throughout this course. }
14... Bd4 15. Rb1 Qxe5 16. Qxe5
{ The best move! I know it seems strange to trade queens after losing a pawn, but the compensation will be very clear. }
16... Bxe5 17. Ba3
{ There is no time to waste, we need to continue attacking. } 17... Bd6 18.
Bxd6 cxd6 19. a4
{ White is down a pawn, but Black has a minor piece problem. The position is very complex and White has more than sufficient compensation. }
19... d5
{ The most logical move in my opinion! Black breaks in the center and wants to trade off their doubled pawns. }
20. a5 { The whole point of playing a4 is to misplace Black's knight. } 20...
Nc8 21. Rfe1
{ Rooks should be on open files, and we now intend Re5 and possibly Re7. White is also threatening to take on d5, when Black would remain with doubled pawns. }
21... Nd6 22. cxd5 { Fixing Black's doubled pawns. } 22... cxd5 23. Rbd1
{ Placing the other rook on a good semi-open file. The position is obviously very difficult for both players, but I believe White has good practical chances. }
