{ Another sac! The moves are pretty intense, but they make sense. We attack the d8-rook that's protecting d7. This move also leads to a beautiful mating idea if Black plays  17...Qxc3? }
17... Qxc3 18. Rxd7 { This is the end! } 18... Rxd7
{ This leads to a forced checkmate. } 19. Bxd7+ Kxd7
{ And now the whole point of the sac! } 20. Qh3+ { It's mate in a few moves. }
20... Ke8 21. Qc8# *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) 8.h4 Qe6 9.g3"]
[Black "9...Nb4 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Qe6
{ This is the favorite reply of many top players. I find it very solid for Black, but it gives White plenty of ways to play for an advantage. The idea of this move is simple: Black wants to be able to develop the f8-bishop next.In exchange, White can get a tempo on Black's queen with Bh3 or Ng5 at some point. Black also refrains from playing ...d6 and ... f6 anytime soon, because then ...Qe6 would have been a waste of time. }
9. g3
{ Another waiting move! This makes sense because of the position of the queen on e6. White's next move will be Bg2, or even better, Bh3! Now Black has multiple interesting replies, but after all of them White will get good fighting chances.   One thing that users might ask is: why am I giving two lines vs @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/7P/8/PPP1QPP1/RNB1KB1R b KQkq h3 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8...Qe6?  Well, both  9.Nd2  and  9.g3  are playable and very interesting for White, and since 8...Qe6 is the preferred move of the top players, I wanted to provide as many possible options for us to fight against such a tough move. The more surprises for our opponent, the more difficult it is for them to prepare against us. I also believe that there are many similaraties and transpositions between both these lines, so it's good for your general knowledge of the 8.h4 variation to study both moves. }
9... Nb4
{ Black opens up several tactical possibilities, for example with continuations like 10...Qg6 and 10...Ba6, and targets c2. This is without a doubt a very complex position, and White needs to be careful. }
10. Bh3
{ This move shows another big advantage of the h4 line, which is the fact that the bishop on h3 is defended by the rook on h1. This is especially good now that the black queen is on e6. We love developing with a free tempo! }
10... Qd5 11. O-O
{ This introduces one of my favorite ideas in the entire course: a beautiful exchange sacrifice for the initiative. }
11... Ba6
{ Black accomplishes their goal of developing the bishop to a6 with a tempo, but White has a gorgeous surprise prepared. }
12. Qd1 Bxf1
{ The only move! Otherwise White wins even more time with  12...--  13.Nc3  . }
13. Qxf1
{ Now finding the best move for White is very difficult, as there is nothing clear for Black to do. Many moves that look natural could immediately lose the game. }
13... Qe4 { The only move, and a very difficult one to find. } 14. Nc3 Qxc2
{ Possibly the only move, and a scary one. Black keeps taking material, and has moved the queen multiple times. It's not very human to feel comfortable as Black here, just continuing to grab material while being so underdeveloped. }
15. Bf4
{ Definitely a move that you should know when playing this line. It's a very difficult idea to find over the board, but the point will become clear as we get deeper in the line. One thing that's simple to understand if that we need to bring the last piece into the attack, so we prepare to develop the a1-rook.   Other moves that have been tried in correspondence games are  15.Bg5  and  15.Be3  . White has won all three games after those moves, which is a very impressive result for such a complex position. }
15... Qxb2
{ 15...Be7  is best, castling as quickly as possible, but White is doing well after  16.Rd1↑  , and after Black castles short White will take on d7 with the rook, with good compensation. }
16. Rd1
{ A beautiful sacrifice! White has too much piece activity, and Black is still figuring out how to get the king out of the center and save the queen at the same time. After all, we are only down an exchange and some pawns, so it's not that bad. }
16... Rd8 17. Bg5
{ Another sac! The moves are pretty intense, but they make sense. We attack the d8-rook that's protecting d7. This move also leads to a beautiful mating idea if Black plays  17...Qxc3? }
17... Be7 18. Bxe7 Kxe7 19. Qc4
{ It's still a very complex position, but a fun one to play as White. We are threatening  19...--  20.Rb1  winning the knight, and also a check on c5 to disconnect Black's rooks. }
19... Nd5
{ A logical move, trying to trade the knights. However, it's completely losing for Black. }
20. Rxd5 cxd5
{ Black needs to try to keep the material advantage. Otherwise they are a minor exchange down while White still has the better position. }
21. Nxd5+ Ke8 22. Qc5
{ Black either gets mated or gives up their queen for our knight. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) 8.h4 a5"]
[Black "9...Nb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 a5
{ One of those moves that prove that 8.h4 is a good waiting move. Now we have to play  9.c4  in order to take advantage of Black's move! }
9. c4 Nb6
{ Not the most popular move, as it doesn't make sense to immediately retreat the knight after playing ...a5. If the whole purpose of playing ...a5 is to play ...Ba6 next, so Black can keep the knight on d5 longer, then why retreat the knight so soon? It's not very logical. }
10. h5
{ With the idea of playing h6! White is also waiting for Black to define their development. For example, a move like  10.b3  will allow Black to play  10...a4!  and it's a bit dangerous as the a8-rook will be targeting our rook on a1.It's also not yet clear if White should develop the knight to c3 or d2. With 10.h5 we are again in waiting mode, waiting to see what Black does and then develop accordingly! }
10... Ba6 11. b3
{ The best and safest way to protect c4. As I've mentioned before, this pawn structure is perfect for making the Ba6 and the Nb6 bad. It also helps White with the development of the bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal. Black's attempt to open the file with  11...a4  is not as powerful anymore because the a6-bishop now blocks the a-file for the rook on a8, making the position more difficult for Black. }
11... O-O-O
{ Usually when Black develops quickly on the queenside, the idea is to target e5 with ...Re8 and then pressure the e5-pawn with ...f6 or ...d6. This means we need to be very careful with protecting the pawn, and even more precise with how we develop our pieces. White also needs to focus on castling as quickly and safely as possible. The sooner we get out of the center with the king, the quicker we can stop any future pin threats on the e-file. }
12. Bb2 { No doubt the most natural developing move. } 12... d5
{ This doesn't help with breaking the blockade on c4. } 13. exd6 { Typical! }
13... Qxd6 14. Nd2
{ Black will never be able to get rid of the c4-pawn, and now both of Black's minor pieces are stuck on the queenside. Black will have to make many moves to get these pieces back in the game. }
*

