1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 a5
{ One of those moves that prove that 8.h4 is a good waiting move. Now we have to play  9.c4  in order to take advantage of Black's move! }
9. c4 Nb6
{ Not the most popular move, as it doesn't make sense to immediately retreat the knight after playing ...a5. If the whole purpose of playing ...a5 is to play ...Ba6 next, so Black can keep the knight on d5 longer, then why retreat the knight so soon? It's not very logical. }
10. h5
{ With the idea of playing h6! White is also waiting for Black to define their development. For example, a move like  10.b3  will allow Black to play  10...a4!  and it's a bit dangerous as the a8-rook will be targeting our rook on a1.It's also not yet clear if White should develop the knight to c3 or d2. With 10.h5 we are again in waiting mode, waiting to see what Black does and then develop accordingly! }
10... Ba6 11. b3
{ The best and safest way to protect c4. As I've mentioned before, this pawn structure is perfect for making the Ba6 and the Nb6 bad. It also helps White with the development of the bishop on the a1-h8 diagonal. Black's attempt to open the file with  11...a4  is not as powerful anymore because the a6-bishop now blocks the a-file for the rook on a8, making the position more difficult for Black. }
11... O-O-O
{ Usually when Black develops quickly on the queenside, the idea is to target e5 with ...Re8 and then pressure the e5-pawn with ...f6 or ...d6. This means we need to be very careful with protecting the pawn, and even more precise with how we develop our pieces. White also needs to focus on castling as quickly and safely as possible. The sooner we get out of the center with the king, the quicker we can stop any future pin threats on the e-file. }
12. Bb2 { No doubt the most natural developing move. } 12... f6
{ Black wants to play ...d5 but is worried about the en passant capture, so they get rid of the e5-pawn first. }
13. Qd2
{ A smart move! Now we are targeting the a5-pawn, and next we will attack the bishop on a6. White doesn't want to open the e-file unless there is a way to control Black's initiative. With this move White gives up the e-pawn in a way that keeps the file closed. }
13... fxe5
{ This move looks good, especially because White's initiative seems to fade away after the upcoming queen trade. }
14. Qxa5 Qb4+
{ It makes sense to trade queens in a complex position like this one.   14...Bb7  15.Nd2↑  followed by long castling. White's initiative is strong because the queens have been kept on the board. }
15. Qxb4 Bxb4+ 16. Bc3
{ Black's central pawns look good at first glance, but in reality it's very difficult to push the pawns successfully because White will get pressure on the d- and e-files. Black still needs to deal with the position of the Ba6 and Nb6. White is simply better coordinated.   16.Nd2!?  is also good for White. White will simply castle long and pressure the d7 and e5-pawns. The Rh1-h3 plan is also still on the cards, plus the g7-pawn remains in trouble. }
16... Bc5 17. a4
{ Targeting the b6-knight to make it even worse by threatening a5. If that happens, the knight will have to go to a8. }
