[Black "9...Ba6 with 10...f6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 a5
{ One of those moves that prove that 8.h4 is a good waiting move. Now we have to play  9.c4  in order to take advantage of Black's move! }
9. c4 Ba6 10. g3
{ With Black's pawn on a5, Rh3 ideas are out of the question since Ra3 is no longer a real threat to Black's a6-bishop. Therefore we move on to developing the f1-bishop to g2 or h3.   10.Nd2!?  , as played by Nepo, is also good! This move is similar to many move orders we see in these lines. Many times you can transpose by changing the move order of g3-Nd2-b3 and so on. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@45@@EndBracket@@ Nepomniachtchi,I @@StartBracket@@2784@@EndBracket@@-Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@ chess24. com INT 2020 }
10... f6
{ This is always a decent move in the 8.h4 variation. Black can always play ...f6 to quickly put pressure on the e5-pawn. In this moment specifically, Black's knight is still on d5, so it's especially good because Black would like us to take on f6 so they can recapture with the knight. This way Black tries to avoid the annoying ...Nb6 retreat. }
11. b3
{ A pawn sacrifice that gives White quick development and good fighting chances.   11.Nd2!?  We keep seeing this move everywhere! That is because it's very flexible and practically always possible. The main thing to remember is that you can always change the move order - usually it will lead to the same thing. }
11... fxe5
{ Black has to take - there is no other move that make sense. It's a free pawn so Black should take it while they can.   11...Qxe5??  This is always a trick to be aware of - the pin on the c4-pawn will be removed.  12.Qxe5+  fxe5  13.cxd5+- }
12. Bb2
{ A more aggressive approach! We want to target the pawn on e5, but it's not clear if we will take it right away or if we will simply continue developing first. Whether we take the pawn will depend on Black's response, and White needs to keep an open mind, not being afraid to play down a pawn for a while. The pin on the e-file pin is something that we need to keep in mind at all times if we decide to get the back the pawn. It might be better to keep the pressure and activity instead of restoring material equality.   12.Nd2!?  is an interesting move to try to stop any chance of Black's ...e4. Unfortunately, it is not easy to do so, and Black can get counterplay by giving the pawn back. White should still have the slightly better chances.  12...O-O-O  13.Bg2  We are just finishing our development and castling! The initiative will flow by itself once we are fully coordinated!  13...e4!  The only move to stop White's initiative! Any other natural developing move is too slow for Black.   13...g6?  14.Ne4±  and White dominates the position with O-O and Bg5 coming.  14.Nxe4  Nf6∞  and the position becomes very unclear; White is not in time to castle due to  15.O-O?!  d5! }
12... e4 13. Qh5+
{ A provocative move. White wants to open the a1-h8 diagonal. } 13... g6 14.
Qe5 Qxe5 15. Bxe5
{ Black is in some difficulty here as multiple pieces are hanging. Play can continue  15...Bb4+!  The only move.  16.Nd2  Bc3!!  The only way Black can escape from having multiple pieces hanging. Now after  17.Bxh8  Bxh8  18.Rc1⩲  White is up an exchange in a position where Black still needs to make some difficult decisions. }
