14... Bb4+
{ This logical move which develops a piece is by far the best continuation for Black. }
15. Nd2
{ Allowing checks, but there is nothing to fear. The white king is safe in the center as the d-file is not open yet. }
15... Bxd2+
{ Notice how forcing this line is for both players, but especially for Black. All it takes is one simple mistake and the game is over. }
16. Kd1
{ 16.Kxd2!?  Black will continue with  16...Qxf2+  and many other checks, but White keeps the bishop pair in return. The position becomes very unclear and the mainline of 16.Kd1 is a little easier. }
16... Qxg7 17. Bxg7 Bc3 { The only move to keep the balance! } 18. Bxc3 Nxc3+
19. Kc2
{ The past several moves were forced from both sides. Now we finally arrive at the key moment of the game, as we end up with an interesting endgame. }
19... Ne4
{ The knight has no other square to go to, so Black tries to make it more difficult for White to regain the piece. }
20. Re1 { White is finally getting the knight back. } 20... O-O
{ Another only move! This is one of the points of this course, some of these lines are close to equality but Black is the one who has to find sequences of difficult moves. In the current era of chess, it's good to set practical problems for your opponent that way.   20...d5  21.f3!  is much worse for Black than the mainline. }
