1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Nb6
{ This move shows a big part of why we play @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h4  : we waited for  8...f6  to play  9.c4  , and now Black will be left with a weak pawn on f6! We always want the black knight to be placed on b6, as a typical problem for Black in the Scotch is bringing that knight back into the game. This theme occurs in many lines throughout this course. }
10. exf6 Qxe2+
{ This was played by Anand. Here Black's position deteriorates very quickly. This move is not very logical as it helps us develop the f1-bishop for free. }
11. Bxe2 gxf6 12. Nc3
{ This is a better version for White compared to 10...gxf6 because White has already developed the Bf1. }
