1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Nb6
{ This move shows a big part of why we play @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h4  : we waited for  8...f6  to play  9.c4  , and now Black will be left with a weak pawn on f6! We always want the black knight to be placed on b6, as a typical problem for Black in the Scotch is bringing that knight back into the game. This theme occurs in many lines throughout this course. }
10. exf6 gxf6 11. Nc3
{ A very useful and smart move! It is best for White if Black takes on e2, as it develops the Bishop for us and speeds up our initiative. While we wait for Black to exchange on e2, we will make as many developing moves as possible. Black should never take on e2 as it makes things even worse for them.   11.Be3⩲  is a more aggressive approach. Avoiding the queen trade is also good for White.  11...d5  12.Nd2⩲  Now White's ideas range from Rc1 to g3 followed by Bg2 and O-O. White has a comfortable game. }
11... Ba6 12. b3 { Protecting the c4-pawn and preparing Bb2. } 12... O-O-O
{ Now Black threatens to move their queen away when our king will remain exposed. It's time to trade queens! }
13. Qxe7 Bxe7 14. Bb2
{ Once again, the endgame is just better for White. Our pieces are more active and we have the better pawn structure. This is a position where we are playing for two results @@StartBracket@@a win or a draw@@EndBracket@@.   14...d5  Black tries to fight for the center and tries to get rid of the doubled pawns on the c-file. This would also open up the diagonal of the bishop on a6 diagonal. It's not good enough, though.  15.cxd5  Targeting the a6 bishop, which means Black is forced to exchange on f1.  15...Bxf1  16.Kxf1!  The best move! Taking with the king allows us to coordinate properly, as the a1-rook can come to e1 now, while the h1-rook can be developed via h3.  16...cxd5  17.Rh3!  ⩲ The activity of the white pieces is very obvious. There is no need to castle anymore. White is clearly better. }
