1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Qb4+ 10. Kd1
{ There is no need to open ourselves up to a pin on c3. With the d-file closed it's very hard for Black to punish White's King. }
10... Ne7 { The only move to keep the material balance. } 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Nc3
{ The white king will go to c2 and that will coordinate White's pieces. It's not unusual for White's king to go this path in the Scotch, especially because Black gave us a tempo by playing ...Qb4+. }
12... d5
{ Opening up the position and fighting for space. As you can see, Black's kingside is very difficult to coordinate. Black needs to play on the queenside or in the center. }
13. cxd5 cxd5 14. Bd2
{ Developing but also creating problems for Black. The powerful Nb5 move is a big threat now.   14...Qxb2??  is simply losing:  15.Rb1  Qa3  16.Rb3  All forced so far.  16...Qc5   16...Qd6  17.Nb5+-  is the same idea but even gains a tempo.  17.Nb5+-  Rc3 is next, and if  17...d4  18.Qf3!  White is completely winning. }
