1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Ba6 { By far the best move, and the only one played by top players. } 10.
Rh3 Nb4
{ A very weird move. The way this move makes sense is that it tries to stop Ra3 from ever happening, but of course it gives White a couple of free tempi. }
11. a3 { Kicking the knight and forcing it to come back to d5. } 11... Nd5
{ The only reason I am including this position is because it was played in a game between two GMs: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Brodsky,D @@StartBracket@@2455@@EndBracket@@-Hong,A @@StartBracket@@2474@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis USA 2021. }
12. Qc2 { Forcing the knight to immediately move again. } 12... Qxe5+
{ Who doesn't like a free pawn right? Well, this is not the right time to get hungry. White's initiative for the pawn will be overwhelming. }
13. Be2 { A simple developing move that blocks the check. } 13... Nf4
{ 13...Ne7?!  is another way Black can play, but it blocks the f8-bishop. All White has to do here is play Nc3 follow by O-O-O and our pieces are just too active. Black will have to deal with development and tactical issues. }
14. Bxf4 { 14.Re3?  Nxg2+-+ } 14... Qxf4
{ It make sense for Black to trade pieces since they are up a pawn. } 15. Re3+
{ Placing the rook on the open e-file. } 15... Kd8 16. g3
{ When you are playing with the initiative, it is always a good idea to make moves that give you free tempi as much as possible. Now the black queen has to make a big decision. There is no good, easy way for Black to continue. Wherever the queen moves, it creates new opportunities for White. }
16... Qh6 17. Qf5
{ This move is very strong. It prevents ...Bc5 and it threatens to continue with the simple Nc3 and Rd1, targeting the d7 weakness. }
