h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Ba6 { By far the best move, and the only one played by top players. } 10.
Rh3 O-O-O 11. Ra3
{ This move is mainly useful when Black has already castled long. You will notice that this is the case anytime in this course that Black has castled and we have the move Ra3 available. }
11... Nb4
{ The only move. Otherwise we just sacrifice on a6 followed by cxd5. } 12. Ra4
{ Threatening a3, which would win the bishop on a6. } 12... Qxe5
{ The only move that can fight for equality! } 13. Qxe5 fxe5 14. Bg5
{ The idea is to chase Black's rook from the d-file before Black can play ...d5. }
14... Nc2+ { There is nothing else for Black. } 15. Kd1
{ The best move! White needs to be able to develop the knight via d2 to avoid losing any time in the future with Black playing d5-d4. Also, putting the king on d2 would give Black an extra check on b4 later. }
15... Nxa1 16. Bxd8 Kxd8 { The only move, otherwise Black loses the game. } 17.
Rxa6
{ By force we've reached an endgame where Black has to play extremely accurate in order to survive. The knight is trapped on a1 and one small mistake could be the end of the game. }
17... Bc5 18. f3
{ White's main goal here is to not let the black rook pentetrate into our position. The black rook is the only piece that can prevent us from executing the idea of Kc1-b1xa1. The move f3 keeps the f-file closed for now and gives us more time. }
18... Rf8 19. Nd2
{ This has never been played before and is interesting for White.   19.Ra5!?  ⩲  This position is all about understanding and clear tactics. The more time you spend on it, the more familiar you become with the ideas and the more chances you have to win. There is no doubt that White has an easier game here, at least I wouldn't be comfortable with a trapped knight on a1. ½-½ @@StartBracket@@60@@EndBracket@@ Erigaisi, A @@StartBracket@@2675@@EndBracket@@ -Van Foreest,L @@StartBracket@@2572@@EndBracket@@ Sharjah 2022 }
19... Rf4 20. Ra5 Bf2 21. h5 { Now White gets to keep the h-pawn. } 21... Rh4
22. Rxe5 Rh1
{ Black's rook has finally reach its goal of pinning the f1-bishop. However, for now the knight remains trapped on a1. }
23. b4
{ Material is equal and Black's only counterplay is on the pin on f1. Even the tiniest mistake will lead to Black being lost very quickly. }
