[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Ba6 { By far the best move, and the only one played by top players. } 10.
Rh3 Nb6
{ The reason I don't like this move is because Black doesn't need to move the knight yet, so why waste an important tempo in the opening? Well, Black removes the knight from the c4 attack and is now ready to take the pawn on e5 or even play ...d5. The knight on b6 also puts pressure on the c4-pawn. So it's not illogical at all - in fact, this move has been played by many GMs. }
11. Nd2 fxe5 12. Re3
{ As always, this is a provoking move! We would like to know what Black is going to do with their king before we put the rook on a3. }
12... d6 { Black defends the pawn on e5 and doesn't castle long just yet. } 13.
g3
{ Playing  13.b3  in this position removes any future chances of Ra3, so we don't want to make that pawn move just yet. I also love  13.g3  because it attempts to develop the bishop on f1, which will target the new weakness on c6. We are playing chess based on our opponent's moves. }
13... Qf7 14. Bg2 Bb7 15. c5
{ A key move! We block the b7-bishop forever and force the knight to move, which gives us a tempo we can really use.   15.f4?  would be a mistake. The opening of the position still benefits Black, so we need to make sure we break the pawn structure when we are ready. Right now White is behind in development, and until we catch up we need to be more patient.  15...O-O-O !  ∓ }
15... Nd5
{ With the black knight sitting on d5, the e4 outpost becomes very important for our own knight since Black cannot kick it away with ...d5. }
16. Rf3
{ Attacking the queen and again playing energetically so Black cannot easily go ...Be7 and ...O-O. We need to be accurate in the way we use our initiative. One of the nice things about the positioning of this rook is that it prevents any future short castling by Black. }
16... Qe6
{ 16...Qd7?  17.Ne4!  ±  is a much better version for White than the mainline. }
17. Ne4
{ Now we eye Ng5 ideas and we also get ready to develop the c1-bishop. This will be followed by O-O-O with full coordination and development. }
17... h6
{ As expected! This is the best way to stop anything related to Ng5 or Bg5. Black is still in need of castling, but we are making it as difficult as possible for them. Right now there is no safe place to go for Black's King and that's the chaos we want to create. }
18. cxd6
{ Definitely a hard move to make. We help Black get rid of their doubled pawns, but there is a dynamic reason for this choice. }
18... Bxd6
{ A strategically weak move. Black is concerned about falling behind in development, but this creates other issues as now they have doubled isolated pawns on the c-file and another isolated pawn on the e-file. These pawns will become long-term targets for our rooks. }
19. Kf1
{ Change of plans! We can actually manually castle short! This is a really cool move, though it's not the only one that gives White an advantage. }
