1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Ba6 { By far the best move, and the only one played by top players. } 10.
Rh3 Nb6
{ The reason I don't like this move is because Black doesn't need to move the knight yet, so why waste an important tempo in the opening? Well, Black removes the knight from the c4 attack and is now ready to take the pawn on e5 or even play ...d5. The knight on b6 also puts pressure on the c4-pawn. So it's not illogical at all - in fact, this move has been played by many GMs. }
11. Nd2 fxe5 12. Re3
{ As always, this is a provoking move! We would like to know what Black is going to do with their king before we put the rook on a3. }
12... d6 { Black defends the pawn on e5 and doesn't castle long just yet. } 13.
g3
{ Playing  13.b3  in this position removes any future chances of Ra3, so we don't want to make that pawn move just yet. I also love  13.g3  because it attempts to develop the bishop on f1, which will target the new weakness on c6. We are playing chess based on our opponent's moves. }
13... Qd7
{ This is by far the most challenging move, as it protects c6 and opens a path for the f8-bishop to develop through e7. At this point long castling is out of the question as long as Ra3 is available, so Black really needs to aim for short castling instead. }
14. Ra3
{ This is an exception to the rule of when to play the typical Ra3. Black is not castled yet, but White forces the bishop to go to c8. This is obviously very uncomfortable for Black, so we take advantage of the possibility. }
14... Bc8
{ 14...Bb7  15.c5!  ↑  A beautiful move! We give up another pawn to create a tripled isolated pawn in Black's position, so Black can't really take this offering. After  15...Nd5  White will play the strong  16.Nc4!  with the idea of  --  17.Na5  . Black is in a very difficult spot. }
15. c5
{ A great strategic move, hoping that Black takes the pawn at some point. }
15... Nd5
{ This knight being on d5 helps secure White's knight a strong spot in the center on e4, from where it it cannot easily be kicked. }
16. Ne4
{ We are still working on bringing all our pieces into the game, and there is no better place for a knight than the center of the board. }
16... Be7
{ Black's number one priority is castling, and this is the fastest way to accomplish that goal. }
17. Qh5+
{ A critical idea! White wants to force the ...g6 pawn move, which creates dark-squared weaknesses and also provides a hook for h4-h5. }
17... g6
{ Black has no other choice than to block the check in this way, weakening their kingside. }
18. Qd1
{ An improvement on a previously played game between GMs. The idea is to have the option of playing Qa4 where the queen will be more active. }
18... O-O
{ Finally Black's king is castled, but they still have much work ahead in order to coordinate and activate their pieces. }
19. Bh6
{ Notice here one of the advantages of our Qh5+ move: it makes this bishop move possible. }
19... Rf7 20. Qa4
{ A big plus of playing Qd1 instead of Qe2. Now we are ready to castle when our initiative will become more clear. }
20... Qe8
{ Another tough move to make for Black, but there is also not much else they can do. This move makes sense because Black wants to develop the c8-bishop. }
21. O-O-O
{ Finishing development. Now we've brought our second rook into the game. The bishop on f1 is next in line. }
21... Bg4 { This is the only downside of long castling for White. } 22. Re1
{ Indirectly looking at the Qe8. Now Black needs to take care of the threat Nxd6! because it uncovers an attack from our queen on the bishop on g4. }
22... Be6 23. Bc4
{ With strong compensation for the extra pawn. First off, Black's extra pawn is a doubled one. Secondly, it's very hard for Black to use their central pawns because they cannot easily be pushed. It's also not easy for Black to move their pieces around as White has a ton of space and more piece activity.  23...dxc5?!  This move is always bad. Having tripled pawns is like being down 2 pawns!  24.Qd1!  Not allowing ...Nb6. now the real target is the pawn on e5. This is one of the reasons we played Re1 and not Rd2 earlier.  24...Qc8  25.Bg5!  ↑  By trading the dark-squared bishops we create new targets for the knight on e4, like the c5-pawn and the g5-square. }
