{ This is the simplest reply! You can opt for a more agressive pawn sac with  11.Nd2  , but if you like endgames  11.exf6  could be your move. }
11... Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Bxc4
{ The only way. Back needs to take on c4, otherwise it gets bad for them really fast. }
13. Re3+
{ A tricky move! Black has to define the king, and there is only one way to go. }
13... Kd8
{ Black's best shot is to keep the King close to their center pawns, as these pawns give Black an extra layer of safety. }
14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. Nc3
{ Again, let's not forget our development. It's also important to consider the pawn structure for a bit. We have a 3v1 on the kingside and 4v2 on the queenside. One of Black's extra pawns on the queenside is doubled which makes it harder for them to push, and this is one of White's small advantages in this endgame. We still need to coordinate our pieces, especially the Ra1 which is not doing anything yet. }
15... a5
{ This might look strange at first, but it's a typical move. Black knows that White is going to play b3 at some point and wants to have the move ...a4 available against it. }
16. Rg3
{ Opening the diagonal of the c1-bishop so we can follow up with Bg5. An interesting detail here is the fact that White doesn't mind trading light-squared bishops. In fact, White doesn't mind trading both pairs of bishops.   16.Re4!?  The idea is to force the bishop trade on e2 so we can retake with the king. This was played recently in ½-½ @@StartBracket@@49@@EndBracket@@ Wieczorek,O  @@StartBracket@@2505@@EndBracket@@-Pasztor,B  @@StartBracket@@2387@@EndBracket@@ Vrnjacka Banja 2023, and White had chances. }
16... Be5 17. Rf3
{ Intending Rf7 or Rf5 in the future and avoiding the bishop attack. This also introduces a new idea of Bf4, to get rid of Black's active e5-bishop. }
17... a4
{ @@StartSquare@@#@@EndSquare@@ Black follows the idea of preventing b3 and now threatens a dangerous move like ...a3.   17...Bxe2?!  18.Kxe2⩲ }
18. Bf4
{ Once the bishops are traded, we don't really have to worry about the move ...a3 anymore. }
18... Bxf4 19. Rxf4 Re8
{ Making things a little more difficult for White.   19...Bxe2?  makes it easier for White to coordinate.  20.Kxe2⩲  Taking with the king is a theme here. The white king needs to assist with the kingside pawn push. }
20. Rd1
{ No doubt this is a difficult endgame, but White has the better pawn structure and our rooks are a bit more active. A long fight is ahead, but I'd rather take White's connected passed pawns over Black's doubled pawns. }
