{ It's now time to bring the rook to the a-file. With the black King on the queenside, this rook is defintely on the right square. we also attack a6 and a7, already creating visible issues in Black's position.   13.Rb3!?  is also very good as it stops Black's king from going to b8 or their queen from going to b4. Moreover, we are now ready to continue developing with Nc3 and O-O-O. A more aggressive idea is to play Qd2-Qa5.  13...d5  14.Nd2  Protecting c4 and trying to castle long.  14...dxc4  15.g3!  ↑  A beautiful move, targeting the h3-c8 diagonal and using the power of the pin on the f1-a6 diagonal. The position is complicated, but White has the initiative for sure. }
13... Qb4+
{ This only helps White. It doesn't take care of the issue with a6 and a7, so with simple play White quickly gets the better position. }
14. Nc3
{ We always need the Knight to come into the game at some point. The more pieces the merrier, and we need all of them to contribute to the attack. Also, with the knight developed, the a1-rook can come to c1 or sometimes we can just castle long to bring the rook to d1. }
14... Bxc4
{ A tactical approach is not good enough to escape from the pressure. } 15.
Qxc4 Qxc4 { Completely forced! } 16. Bxc4 Bxa3
{ This is the reason Black sacrificed on c4. } 17. Ba6+
{ White's bishop pair is too strong and Black cannot compensate with the extra pawns. This a nice touch to the position, which increases our attack. After  17...Kb8  18.bxa3  White is clearly better. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) 8.h4 f6"]
[Black "9...Ba6 with 10...fxe5 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6
{ This is the most complicated line against 8.h4! Against this move we will use the famous Rh3 idea! What makes this position so complex is that White will sacrifice a pawn for the initiative. For humans this is always difficult to understand, so if you practice the lines in this chapter and truly understand the arising positions, your opponents will have a really tough time. }
9. c4 Ba6 { By far the best move, and the only one played by top players. } 10.
Rh3 fxe5 11. Bg5
{ This move shows one of the many advantages of h4! It defends the Bg5 if needed, like in this case. }
11... Nf6 { The only decent move to get a good fight. } 12. Re3
{ The classic waiting move of this line. We keep open the possibility of putting the rook on a3 in case Black castles long.   12.Nd2!?  is also possible and interesting for White. One of the reasons I am mentioning this option is to have more ways to play and surprise your opponent. The idea here is simple: White wants to castle long and place the rook on a3 or e3. Then the f1-bishop can be developed to g2/h3 after g3 or on the f1-a6 diagonal. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Espinosa Veloz, E @@StartBracket@@2485@@EndBracket@@-Novoselski,Z @@StartBracket@@2324@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2021 }
12... O-O-O 13. Ra3
{ It's now time to bring the rook to the a-file. With the black King on the queenside, this rook is defintely on the right square. we also attack a6 and a7, already creating visible issues in Black's position.   13.Rb3!?  is also very good as it stops Black's king from going to b8 or their queen from going to b4. Moreover, we are now ready to continue developing with Nc3 and O-O-O. A more aggressive idea is to play Qd2-Qa5.  13...d5  14.Nd2  Protecting c4 and trying to castle long.  14...dxc4  15.g3!  ↑  A beautiful move, targeting the h3-c8 diagonal and using the power of the pin on the f1-a6 diagonal. The position is complicated, but White has the initiative for sure. }
13... Qb4+
{ This only helps White. It doesn't take care of the issue with a6 and a7, so with simple play White quickly gets the better position. }
14. Nc3
{ We always need the Knight to come into the game at some point. The more pieces the merrier, and we need all of them to contribute to the attack. Also, with the knight developed, the a1-rook can come to c1 or sometimes we can just castle long to bring the rook to d1. }
14... Bb7
{ Black cannot do anything else, the bishop will have to retreat to b7 at some point. }
15. Rb3
{ Now it is time to target the b7-bishop and get out of the potential threat on the a3-f8 diagonal.   15.O-O-O !?  is also very good and was played in the game 0-1 @@StartBracket@@63@@EndBracket@@ Morozevich,A @@StartBracket@@2711@@EndBracket@@-Adhiban,B @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@ Berlin 2015. }
15... Qa5
{ The black queen must stay on the queenside. Otherwise, what was the point of the giving the check on b4? }
16. Bd2
{ A powerful discovered attack is on the horizon. We are simply adjusting to the new position of Black's queen, using as many of our pieces as possible. Things are falling apart very quickly for Black now. }
16... Qa6 17. O-O-O
{ This simple approach is good enough, getting our king out of the center and threatening to take on e5. After we move the queen on e2, the bishop on f1 will directly target Black's queen on a6, with more difficult decisions to come for Black.   17...c5  Trying to stop White's future c5 and opening the diagonal for the Bb7.  18.g4!  +-  Again, there is no reason to rush. g5 is next followed by Bh3 and Black's pieces are not able to do anything about it. It's hard to activate Black's pieces in any reasonable way at all. }
