{ It's now time to bring the rook to the a-file. With the black King on the queenside, this rook is defintely on the right square. we also attack a6 and a7, already creating visible issues in Black's position.   13.Rb3!?  is also very good as it stops Black's king from going to b8 or their queen from going to b4. Moreover, we are now ready to continue developing with Nc3 and O-O-O. A more aggressive idea is to play Qd2-Qa5.  13...d5  14.Nd2  Protecting c4 and trying to castle long.  14...dxc4  15.g3!  ↑  A beautiful move, targeting the h3-c8 diagonal and using the power of the pin on the f1-a6 diagonal. The position is complicated, but White has the initiative for sure. }
13... Bb7 { Practically the only move! } 14. Nc3
{ 14.Nd2!?  is another possible move that hasn't been played so far. It's very logical. White tries to castle long and play for an easy attack. }
14... d5
{ A logical move that tries to use Black's extra pawn in the center to fight for space, but it comes with big issues. One of them is the opening of the c-file.   14...Qf7  15.Rb3!  ↑  Here the rook is better on b3! This way it doesn't allow the move ...Kb8, and it brings Rxb7 sacrifices into the position.   14...Qe6  15.Rb3! }
15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rb3
{ Here we go again with this move! There are a lot of tactical ideas that are based on the rook being on the b-file. This is especially true because of the position of the bishop on b7 and the possibility of Black's king going to b8.Now Black has many possible moves, but they all give up something. White's initiative will become more clear as you go through the analysis. }
16... c6 17. Rc1
{ Control of the c-file and the activity of the rook is currently more important than castling. The white king is perfectly safe in the center. Now White has ideas like Nb5 or Na4-c5. The rook also targets c6 and the king on c8. }
17... Kb8
{ The best move, and an easy one to make because it looks scary to stay on c8 with White's rook being on c1. }
18. Na4
{ All the white pieces are working together for the initiative. The Knight is threatening to come to c5 with a winning attack, and Black needs to defend against this immediately.   18.Qa6!?  This move shows another idea in this position, as the queen can be maneuvered to a4 with a scary attack on Black's king. This will also open the f1-Bishop, allowing White to bring more pieces into the attack.  18...Qc7  19.Qa4!  ↑ }
18... Qc7
{ Defending against Nc5 followed by disaster on b7 by opening the f8-bishop's diagonal. }
19. Nc5 Bxc5 20. Rxc5
{ It's clear who has the initiative if you look at White's pieces and compare them to Black's. The worst of all is the bishop on b7, but also both of Black's rooks are not active and don't have much of a future either.   An example of a move that attempts to simplify is  20...h6  . Now White has a quick way of punishing this move.  21.Bxf6!  gxf6  22.Qa6!  White threatens to take on c6 and finish the game.  22...Ka8  The only move to survive.  23.Qa4!!  ±  Followed by Ba6 or Ra3. It's going to be very sad for Black. }
