[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) 8.h4 d6"]
[Black "10...Qxe2+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 d6
{ This is a very solid line. Black wants to trade queens and get into an endgame. The Scotch endgames are usually very good for White, though. The exchanges in the center will usually leave Black with some pawn weaknesses. }
9. c4
{ Once again, as soon as Black defines the way they are playing the position, we play c4 to misplace their knight. }
9... Nb6 10. exd6 Qxe2+
{ If Black exchanges on e2 this is always better for us than White exchanging on e7, as we get to develop our f1-bishop to e2 for free. }
11. Bxe2 cxd6
{ 11...Bxd6?!  Black fixes their pawn structure and now there is no way of getting rid of the doubled c-pawns. In the endgame White will have an enduring advantage after  12.Nc3⩲  . }
12. Bf3
{ This move is very important because we want the upper hand in putting pressure on Black's weak pawns, so we target c6 as soon as possible in order to force Black to place their bishop passively on d7. This is a typical looking Scotch endgame. Black will suffer to obtain a draw thanks to the weak pawn structure combined with their lack of activity.This position represents a good and reachable goal for a Scotch player. We will be shooting for two results, a draw or a win, and that's a nice advantage to have in any opening you play nowdays.   12.Nc3!?  is also possible, but not as active as the mainline. Black could now play  12...Be6  13.Bf3  or  13.b3  with a slight edge for White. }
12... d5 13. cxd5
{ The simplest way to create an isolated pawn for Black no matter what. } 13...
Nxd5
{ 13...cxd5?!  14.Nc3⩲  would be very bad for Black since the Nb6 is poorly placed. That's why taking with the knight on d5 is best. }
14. Nc3
{ Black's c-pawn will be isolated for the whole game, whether it remains on the c-file or ends up on the d-file after an exchange. }
