[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 8.h4 h6"]
[Black "9...Ba6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 h6
{ This move is not very logical because it justifies the h4 move immediately. This is because we can just play as in the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.c4  line, but with the moves h4 and ...h6 included, which can only benefit White. Many times in the  8.c4  complex Black plays moves like ...g6 or ...g5, the latter of which isn't possible any longer. Also, now we have the chance to play Rh3 in some lines, which is normally not possible after  8.c4  . The only good thing about ...h6 from Black's perspective is that it stops a possible h5-h6 from White, as well as Bg5 ideas. }
9. c4 Ba6
{ This move provides an extra justification for White's 8.h4, so it doesn't help Black at all. }
10. Rh3
{ Not the only good move,  10.b3  and  10.Qe4  are also both great moves. However, with  10.Rh3  we take advantage of having played h4 and Black having played ...Ba6 early. }
10... O-O-O 11. Ra3
{ This forces Black to play ...Nb4, as otherwise we carry out the strong threat of  11...--  12.Rxa6  followed by  --  13.cxd5  . }
11... Nb4 12. Ra4
{ This is an improved version of the 8.h4 f6 line, but with ...h6 instead of ...f6. White is just better. I would recommend looking into the 8...f6 line to get a deeper understanding of this unusual line.The main problem for Black right now is: how are they going to stop  12...--  13.a3  which wins material right away? Will they retreat the Nb4 to a6? There is just no good way for Black to deal with all the problems in this position. In the analogous position with the pawn on f6 instead of h6, at least they could take with the queen on e5 and escape into a close to equal endgame. }
12... Qxh4
{ I've included some analysis of this move because it's one of the few moves Black has in this 8...h6 line that aren't available to them in the analogous 8...f6 line. }
13. Nc3 Qxc4 { This is a blunder. Now White's initiative becomes more clear. }
14. Qxc4 Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Nc2+
{ There is nothing else. Black needs to grab the rook before it's too late. }
16. Kd1 { All forced. } 16... Nxa1 17. Bxf7
{ Black has many issues here. Not only do we have the bishop pair and the initiative, but the Knight on a1 is also trapped. }
*

