{ This is an improved version of the 8.h4 f6 line, but with ...h6 instead of ...f6. White is just better. I would recommend looking into the 8...f6 line to get a deeper understanding of this unusual line.The main problem for Black right now is: how are they going to stop  12...--  13.a3  which wins material right away? Will they retreat the Nb4 to a6? There is just no good way for Black to deal with all the problems in this position. In the analogous position with the pawn on f6 instead of h6, at least they could take with the queen on e5 and escape into a close to equal endgame. }
12... Qxh4
{ I've included some analysis of this move because it's one of the few moves Black has in this 8...h6 line that aren't available to them in the analogous 8...f6 line. }
13. Nc3 d5 14. Rxa6 dxc4 15. Ra4 { An amazing defensive move! } 15... Nd3+ 16.
Qxd3 Rxd3 17. Bxd3
{ White is up material, and after some good defensive moves White should be better. }
17... Bc5 18. Ne4 { And now taking the bishop is a blunder. } 18... cxd3 19.
Nd6+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 8.h4 h6"]
[Black "9...Ba6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 h6
{ This move is not very logical because it justifies the h4 move immediately. This is because we can just play as in the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.c4  line, but with the moves h4 and ...h6 included, which can only benefit White. Many times in the  8.c4  complex Black plays moves like ...g6 or ...g5, the latter of which isn't possible any longer. Also, now we have the chance to play Rh3 in some lines, which is normally not possible after  8.c4  . The only good thing about ...h6 from Black's perspective is that it stops a possible h5-h6 from White, as well as Bg5 ideas. }
9. c4 Ba6
{ This move provides an extra justification for White's 8.h4, so it doesn't help Black at all. }
10. Rh3
{ Not the only good move,  10.b3  and  10.Qe4  are also both great moves. However, with  10.Rh3  we take advantage of having played h4 and Black having played ...Ba6 early. }
10... Nb6 11. Nd2
{ Other moves like  11.b3  are also good, but we want to leave the third rank open for the rook in case we want to play Ra3. While we keep the option open for a potential Ra3, we develop an important piece and give Black the chance to let us know how they are intending to develop. This move is always the most flexible one of all! }
11... g6
{ Black understands that castling long is very dangerous, so they try to go short instead. This move has a problem of its own: it weakens the f6-square, and we are ready to exploit that with our knight.   11...O-O-O ?!  As we know from other variations, the moment Black plays ...O-O-O, we instantly swing the rook over!  12.Ra3!!  ±  Our waiting has worked! The rook is in the best possible place! }
12. Ra3 { Chasing Black's bishop away so it doesn't pressure c4 any longer. }
12... Bb7 13. Ne4 { The incoming Nf6 is difficult for Black to deal with. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 8.h4 h6"]
[Black "9...Nb6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 h6
{ This move is not very logical because it justifies the h4 move immediately. This is because we can just play as in the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.c4  line, but with the moves h4 and ...h6 included, which can only benefit White. Many times in the  8.c4  complex Black plays moves like ...g6 or ...g5, the latter of which isn't possible any longer. Also, now we have the chance to play Rh3 in some lines, which is normally not possible after  8.c4  . The only good thing about ...h6 from Black's perspective is that it stops a possible h5-h6 from White, as well as Bg5 ideas. }
9. c4 Nb6
{ As we've seen,  9...Ba6  runs into  10.Rh3  followed by Ra3, so it makes more sense for Black to retreat the knight immediately. }
10. Nc3
{ The best move. This is the most natural way for the white knight to be developed whenever it is possible, and since the black knight is not on d5 anymore, we take advantage of this possibility.   10.g3!?  All of the regular Scotch moves are possible here:  10.Nd2!?  or  10.b3!?  or  10.g3!?  are also playable and good for White. In fact you might play one, and then your next move is the other one. There is no wrong way of developing here. As soon as you make at least some of these moves, White is doing okay. Still, I personally prefer  10.Nc3  . }
10... Qe6
{ What we are seeing here is a very old line of the regular 8.c4, but with the moves h4 and ...h6 included. This can only favor White as we will have an initiative and attack on the kingside. }
11. Bd2
{ This move is the most flexible! We don't define the position of our queen just yet and give Black time to make a choice. We also haven't shown whether we are going to castle short or long. We have plenty of options here, and that's the point.   11.Qe4!?  If you omit the moves 8.h4 h6, you will find many games from super GMs  @@StartBracket@@including Kasparov@@EndBracket@@ with this position as a reference on how to play with 11.Qe4. The position is good for White, but I prefer 11.Bd2.  11...Bb4   11...d5?!  This move doesn't help. Black has played ...Qe6 only to later trade the queens anyway. If this was the idea all along, it would have been better to play ...d6 or ...d5 before having played ...Qe6.  12.exd6⩲  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Mihok, O @@StartBracket@@2507@@EndBracket@@-Kreisl, R @@StartBracket@@2448@@EndBracket@@ Austria 2017@@EndBracket@@  12.Bd2⩲ }
11... d5 12. cxd5
{ A powerful move! Taking advantage of the fact that Black cannot retake with the c-pawn.   12.exd6⩲  The typical Scotch endgame after the en passant trade on d6 is always good for White too. }
12... cxd5 13. Nb5
{ With Rc1 coming to increase the pressure on c7, Black has to make some very awkward moves to keep it all together. }
*

