[White "6) 8.h4 h6"]
[Black "9...Nb6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 h6
{ This move is not very logical because it justifies the h4 move immediately. This is because we can just play as in the @@StartFEN@@r1b1kb1r/p1ppqppp/2p5/3nP3/8/8/PPP1QPPP/RNB1KB1R w KQkq - 3 8@@EndFEN@@  8.c4  line, but with the moves h4 and ...h6 included, which can only benefit White. Many times in the  8.c4  complex Black plays moves like ...g6 or ...g5, the latter of which isn't possible any longer. Also, now we have the chance to play Rh3 in some lines, which is normally not possible after  8.c4  . The only good thing about ...h6 from Black's perspective is that it stops a possible h5-h6 from White, as well as Bg5 ideas. }
9. c4 Nb6
{ As we've seen,  9...Ba6  runs into  10.Rh3  followed by Ra3, so it makes more sense for Black to retreat the knight immediately. }
10. Nc3
{ The best move. This is the most natural way for the white knight to be developed whenever it is possible, and since the black knight is not on d5 anymore, we take advantage of this possibility.   10.g3!?  All of the regular Scotch moves are possible here:  10.Nd2!?  or  10.b3!?  or  10.g3!?  are also playable and good for White. In fact you might play one, and then your next move is the other one. There is no wrong way of developing here. As soon as you make at least some of these moves, White is doing okay. Still, I personally prefer  10.Nc3  . }
10... Qe6
{ What we are seeing here is a very old line of the regular 8.c4, but with the moves h4 and ...h6 included. This can only favor White as we will have an initiative and attack on the kingside. }
11. Bd2
{ This move is the most flexible! We don't define the position of our queen just yet and give Black time to make a choice. We also haven't shown whether we are going to castle short or long. We have plenty of options here, and that's the point.   11.Qe4!?  If you omit the moves 8.h4 h6, you will find many games from super GMs  @@StartBracket@@including Kasparov@@EndBracket@@ with this position as a reference on how to play with 11.Qe4. The position is good for White, but I prefer 11.Bd2.  11...Bb4   11...d5?!  This move doesn't help. Black has played ...Qe6 only to later trade the queens anyway. If this was the idea all along, it would have been better to play ...d6 or ...d5 before having played ...Qe6.  12.exd6⩲  ½-½ @@StartBracket@@40@@EndBracket@@ Mihok, O @@StartBracket@@2507@@EndBracket@@-Kreisl, R @@StartBracket@@2448@@EndBracket@@ Austria 2017@@EndBracket@@  12.Bd2⩲ }
11... Bb4
{ This is the move that gives White the most difficulties. Black is trying to get castled quickly in order to put pressure on e5, while keeping ...Ba6 as an option. Black's main goal is to eventually play ...d5.   11...Ba6  12.b3⩲ }
12. O-O-O
{ An important move to achieve, because now we are out of the center and safe, we are ready to launch an attack on the kingside and we are ready to fight in the center as well. }
12... Ba6 13. b3 O-O
{ At this point we see one of the biggest advantages of having included h4 and ...h6 early in the opening: we suddenly have a potent attack on the kingside. Usually pawn moves in front of the king help the attacking side, and that's definitely the case for us here. }
14. g4
{ After this strong attacking move, Black will most likely have to play  14...d5  with the idea of fighting back in the center as quickly as possible. This is a typical defensive strategy in chess: when you are getting attacked on the flank, break in the center! After  14...d5  we will answer  15.exd6  with a slightly better endgame. }
*

