1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 g6 { Not a move we are expecting to see after 8.h4. } 9. c4 Ba6
{ This is another position that White would have never gotten in the 8.c4 line. Normally, you would play this position without the moves h4 and ...g6 included. This benefits White, as you will see later. }
10. Rh3
{ Again the threat is Ra3! This is an idea that we've seen many times throughout the course. The Rh3 move is a direct response to Black playing ...Ba6. }
10... Bg7
{ Not paying attention to your opponent's threats is not a good way to play chess. }
11. Ra3 Nb4
{ Even though many of you will likely never encounter this position, the tactical ideas of it can be used in many different lines in the 8.h4 variation. With that said, it's important to understand the reasoning behind each move. }
12. Ra4 { White threatens a3, winning a piece. } 12... O-O
{ 12...Bc8  13.Bg5!  ±  Everything is coming together to prove how good 8.h4 was. }
13. Bg5
{ The h4-pawn was hanging, but that's not why we play Bg5. We are trying to finish our development and get the king out of the center. We also still have the a3 move at some point. }
13... Nd3+
{ A good try! Black sacrifices the Knight so that they can play ...Qxe5+ followed by ...Qxb2.   13...Qc5  14.a3+- }
14. Kd1
{ A crushing move! Now Black loses a piece for some pawns, which turns out not to be enough compensation. }
14... Qxe5 15. Qxe5
{ With our king in the center it is a good idea to trade queens. } 15... Bxe5
16. Bxd3 Bxc4
{ Black tries to get as many pawns as possible to compensate.  16...Bxb2  would be easier for White after  17.Rxa6+- }
17. Rxc4 Bxb2 18. Bf6
{ The key move! At this point White will be able to keep an extra knight for three pawns, but the real issue with those pawns is that one of them is doubled and they are very difficult to push. }
