[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 g6 { Not a move we are expecting to see after 8.h4. } 9. c4 Ba6
{ This is another position that White would have never gotten in the 8.c4 line. Normally, you would play this position without the moves h4 and ...g6 included. This benefits White, as you will see later. }
10. Rh3
{ Again the threat is Ra3! This is an idea that we've seen many times throughout the course. The Rh3 move is a direct response to Black playing ...Ba6. }
10... Nb6
{ Taking care of the threat of Ra3, since the knight on d5 is not under attack anymore. This also targets c4, which forces White to make a defensive move. }
11. b3
{ The best way to defend the c4-pawn.  11.Nd2  here would not be as good because it blocks us from playing Bg5. The only downside of  11.b3  is that it blocks Ra3, but since Black's knight is not on d5 anymore and Black's king has not castled long, we don't really want to put the rook on a3 anyway. Instead, we firmly protect c4 and give our bishop on c1 the opportunity of developing to b2 as well. }
11... Bg7
{ Black is almost done coordinating and is ready to castle short, which leads to some problems for our e5-pawn. White has no time to waste! }
12. Bg5
{ A very important move which is only possible thanks to 8.h4. The idea is to define the position of Black's queen so we can play accordingly. We also develop the bishop with tempo and speed up our coordination. Another idea of this move is to stop Black from castling long, and we also take advantage of the fact that Black cannot yet touch the e5-pawn. }
12... Qb4+ 13. Qd2
{ Now the e5-pawn is indirectly protected by our rook, which is ready for a pin on e3! A Scotch player needs to be ready to switch from a tactical position to an endgame at any point in the game. After  13...Qxd2+  14.Nxd2  White is ready to continue with Bf6 and long castling with a nice endgame. }
*

