10... Nb6
{ Taking care of the threat of Ra3, since the knight on d5 is not under attack anymore. This also targets c4, which forces White to make a defensive move. }
11. b3
{ The best way to defend the c4-pawn.  11.Nd2  here would not be as good because it blocks us from playing Bg5. The only downside of  11.b3  is that it blocks Ra3, but since Black's knight is not on d5 anymore and Black's king has not castled long, we don't really want to put the rook on a3 anyway. Instead, we firmly protect c4 and give our bishop on c1 the opportunity of developing to b2 as well. }
11... Bg7
{ Black is almost done coordinating and is ready to castle short, which leads to some problems for our e5-pawn. White has no time to waste! }
12. Bg5
{ A very important move which is only possible thanks to 8.h4. The idea is to define the position of Black's queen so we can play accordingly. We also develop the bishop with tempo and speed up our coordination. Another idea of this move is to stop Black from castling long, and we also take advantage of the fact that Black cannot yet touch the e5-pawn. }
12... Qe6
{ 12...f6?  is just horrible for Black after  13.exf6+-  since they can't retake on f6 due to the queen being pinned on the e-file. }
13. Re3 { Keeping everything together. } 13... O-O 14. Nc3
{ White is ready to castle long. As soon as Black plays ...d5, we need to be ready to take en passant on d6. }
14... d6
{ The more precise way for Black as it avoids giving us extra possibilities. Black is trying to remove the pawn on e5, so White is forced to take on d6 right away.   14...d5?!  is the same as 14...d6 but gives White an extra possibility in the form of  15.cxd5!?  , which creates other challenges for Black. However, we can simply transpose to the mainline of this chapter with  15.exd6  so I recommend doing that. }
15. exd6 { The simplest and most logical way of playing. } 15... Qxd6
{ Now we finally get some clarity when it comes to the pawn structure. It's obvious that White has a an edge thanks to Black's doubled c-pawns, but we still need to finish developing and castle. On the other hand, the a2-b3-c4 structure is strong and very important in order to keep the a6-bishop and b6-knight out of the game. Currently Black's main activity is based on the open d- and e-files that can be used by their rooks. }
16. Qd2
{ A beautiful move that attempts to solve White's main problem, which is that we were not able to castle long. Now Black has to be extremely precise to fight for equality, as their queenside minor pieces are poorly placed and their pawn structure could become a permanent problem. }
