[White "8) 8.h4 Bb7 - The Magnus Line"]
[Black "Alternative 10.Rh3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Bb7
{ This was played by Magnus Carlsen and it's a logical move. Black doesn't want to waste time trying for ...Ba6 anymore. This move will be follow by O-O-O and either ...f6 or ...d6, putting pressure on the e5-pawn. }
9. c4
{ Now that Black isn't going to play ...Ba6 anymore, let's carry out c4 right away. }
9... Nb6 10. Rh3 { Played by Hikaru is also good. } 10... Qe6
{ 10...O-O-O  11.a4!  → } 11. Nc3
{ With the bishop on b7 and not a6 and Black's queen on e6 instead of e7, the move Ra3 is neither possible nor strong, so we develop knight to c3 to control a future ...d5 from Black and keep the c1-h6 diagonal open for the bishop's convenience.   11.f4?!  is not necessary yet. We want to play f4 only once the e5-pawn is attacked. ½-  @@StartBracket@@73@@EndBracket@@ ½ @@StartBracket@@73@@EndBracket@@ Nakamura,H @@StartBracket@@2781@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2837@@EndBracket@@ London 2017 }
11... O-O-O 12. Bd2 Ba6
{ A strong idea that is difficult to find, forcing us to play b3, weakening the dark squares on the queenside.   12...Re8?!  13.Re3!  ⩲ }
13. b3 Ba3
{ Now Black stops White from castling long, creating some issues for our coordination. }
14. Rd1 Rhe8 15. Re3
{ White has kept everything together, and now once we make it to f1 with our king, we are doing great. }
