[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 4...Nf6 with 6...Nd5 & 6...Ne4"]
[Black "6...Ne4 7.Nd2 Nc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Ne4 7. Nd2
{ My favorite approach! We developed and offered a trade for a piece that has moved twice already. We are also ready to retake with the bishop and develop another piece.   7.Qf3!?  An original approach played by Kamsky many years ago. Quickly targets the hanging knight on e4 and coordinates the queen for future pressure on g7.  7...Ng5  8.Qg3!  Continuing to attack the knight so we can speed up development.  8...Ne6  Now White is ready to develop and castle short.  9.Bd3⩲  Kamsky-Kortschnoj, Buenos Aires 1993. }
7... Nc5 8. Nb3
{ We continue the coordination of our pieces, it's important to use all of them. With this move, we free up the c1-bishop for development and offer Black a tricky trade. }
8... Be7 9. Qg4
{ As typical in the scotch, plenty of times we switch from short castle to long castle, depending on how safe we feel on the respective side. Also, depending on how much attack can we create on Black's King. }
9... g6 10. Qf3
{ Getting out of the c8-h3 diagonal and stopping d5. We are now ready to continue our development.   10.Bh6?!  d5!  We don't need to allow this. }
10... O-O 11. Be3
{ Again the importance of developing with tempi! We attack the Nc5 and force Black to decide. We know that taking on b3 is not good, so what can Black do now?   11.Bh6?!  is also good, but it forces Black to move the rook to where they want.  11...Re8!⩲ }
11... Ne6
{ Now we switch and castle long because Black's pieces are too passive and there is no way to create an attack on the queenside for Black. }
12. O-O-O
{ White's initiative is too quick! In just two moves, h4-h5, Black is in big trouble. The Rd1 is also nice because it limits Black's break on d5 or d6. }
*

