[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Ne4 7. Nd2
{ My favorite approach! We developed and offered a trade for a piece that has moved twice already. We are also ready to retake with the bishop and develop another piece.   7.Qf3!?  An original approach played by Kamsky many years ago. Quickly targets the hanging knight on e4 and coordinates the queen for future pressure on g7.  7...Ng5  8.Qg3!  Continuing to attack the knight so we can speed up development.  8...Ne6  Now White is ready to develop and castle short.  9.Bd3⩲  Kamsky-Kortschnoj, Buenos Aires 1993. }
7... Nxd2
{ This is the only move! It's difficult to make sense of anything else.   7...d5?  Horrible decision about the pawn structure!  8.Nxe4  dxe4+-  Black has too many weaknesses, but especially the e4-pawn and the king sitting on d8 are tough to swallow.  9.Qxd8+  Kxxd8  10.Be3+- }
8. Bxd2 d5
{ The great Korchnoi played this some years ago, but the position is too easy for White. He ended up losing to Paco Vallejo. }
9. Bd3 { Nothing more natural than this move! } 9... Qh4 10. Be3
{ This is a weird but critical move to increase our advantage. We don't want Black's f8 bishop to be placed on c5, so we cut it off. Vallejo instead played the most natural move with a comfortable play!   10.O-O⩲  Vallejo Pons-Kortschnoj, Vera 2004. }
10... Qb4+
{ This the downside of this move! But we aren't concerned about pawns, Black's position only gets worse by taking on b2. }
11. c3 Qxb2 12. O-O
{ White's initiative is huge! Specially if you take the other pawn on c3, in which case we follow with Rc1 and target the double c-pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) 4...Nf6 with 6...Nd5 & 6...Ne4"]
[Black "6...Nd5 7.c4 Bb4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Nd5
{ A bit of a surprise move! Plenty of times this comes as a premove on online chess or simply Black got the order wrong, but luckily for them, it's an acceptable move. There was no point for White to play Qe2 because Black didn't force us to protect e5 so we took advantage of it and quickly kicked the knight. }
7. c4
{ We obviously don't like the knight on d5, and we want to define it as soon as possible. This allows us to move quickly into developing and with more control of the space. }
7... Bb4+
{ A logical move! We all like checks, and this is not an exception. Black tries to develop with tempo. This move will only make things easier for White! }
8. Bd2 { The best way to coordinate and to accelerate development. } 8... Bxd2+
9. Qxd2
{ Taking with the queen limits Black's choices with the knight and leaves the Nb1 alone so it can go to c3. The Qd2 is also best for putting pressure on the d-pawn. }
9... Ne7
{ Since the Black bishop is no longer on f8, Black decides to make the knight more active than b6. At the same time, the knight now blocks the e-file, which means it will have to be moved again. }
10. Nc3
{ Our development doesn't stop, we are focus on a quick long castle to be able to defend the e5-pawn and pressure the weak pawn d7. }
10... Ng6
{ 10...d5?  Wrong time to try this break.  11.exd6!  Qxd6  12.O-O-O±   11...cxd6  12.O-O-O+- }
11. O-O-O
{ We long castle anyway! Speeding up the pressure on the d-file, and we are ready to pin the knight if Black decides to take on e5. King's safety is also not an issue for White, since the b-file can easily be blocked with b3. Black has an issue finding a place for the c8-bishop to play. The typical break on d5 won't be possible for a while. }
