9... Nb6 10. Nc3 O-O
{ Black needs to target e5 quickly, and the rook is the best piece for this job.   10...Qe7  Not the best way to target that pawn, specially if you are not castled yet!  11.O-O-O!± }
11. O-O-O Qe7 12. Qd4
{ Attempting to play 13. c5 with decisive advantage. On top of the tactical challenge, Black needs to find the best way to pressure the e5-pawn.   It's important to notice that  12...d5  or  12...d6  will simply lose a pawn after  13.exd6  .   @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/p1ppqppp/1np5/4P3/2P5/2N5/PP1Q1PPP/2KR1B1R w - - 5 12@@EndFEN@@  12.f4!?⩲  Chigaev-Paravyan, Lichess.org 2020. }
12... Re8
{ 12...f6?  Black targets e5 and tries to take control of the center.  13.exf6!  Qxf6  14.c5!  +-  Followed by 15. Bc4 after  14...Nd5  and White will eventually win a pawn.   12...c5  Probably Black's best move, but it doesn't really solve anything.  13.Qe4  f5  14.Qf4!  ⩲ }
13. Bd3 Qxe5 { 13...d5  14.exd6!  cxd6  15.Rhe1⩲ } 14. Rhe1 Qxe1
{ 14...Qxd4??  15.Rxe8# } 15. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 16. Kd2
{ Two rooks are usually better than a queen but, usually, that depends on how strong is the attack of the queen to the king. In this case, the white queen has an obvious attack on the black king because it's combined with the bishop, the knight, and the kingside pawns. Making this very dangerous for Black. }
