[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Nd5
{ A bit of a surprise move! Plenty of times this comes as a premove on online chess or simply Black got the order wrong, but luckily for them, it's an acceptable move. There was no point for White to play Qe2 because Black didn't force us to protect e5 so we took advantage of it and quickly kicked the knight. }
7. c4
{ We obviously don't like the knight on d5, and we want to define it as soon as possible. This allows us to move quickly into developing and with more control of the space. }
7... Nb6 8. Bd3
{ I like the simplicity of this move, we just want to short castle and play with the pawn structure advantage. Coordinating is still our top priority.   8.Be3!?  ⩲ A more complex development is also great for White!  8...Bb4+  9.Nd2!  ⩲  This looks as good as the main line! White will follow with Bd3 or Qc2 or both, then castle O-O or O-O-O. The Black bishop on b4 at that time will be useless.  9...O-O  10.Bd3!  Re8  Here we don't have time to castle long, but that's ok!  11.O-O !  ±  Rxe5  12.Nf3↑ }
8... Bb4+ 9. Nc3
{ We want to prove to Black that it's too late for the check on b4. As soon as we short castle the Bb4 will be of no use.   9.Bd2!?  Bxd2+  10.Nxd2⩲  Corrales Jimenez-Paravyan, Lichess.org 2020.   9.Nd2!  ⩲ is also a great move! }
9... d5
{ 9...Bxc3+?  Giving up the bishop pair for the double pawns doesn't help either!  10.bxc3± }
10. exd6 { The usual en-passant. } 10... cxd6 11. O-O
{ Now that we are castled, we are ready to coordinate and put pressure on the d-file. }
11... O-O 12. Qc2
{ And White won a rather easy game! Firouzja-Bosiocic, Bandar e Anzali 2019. }
