14... Be6 15. Be2 d5
{ This leads to the exchange of many pieces, but it leaves our bishop pair on the board, and that's all we should really care about. The resulting endgame is really tough for Black. Deac won an instructive blitz game from this position. }
16. exd5 Nxd5
{ Taking with the bishop makes no sense as it doesn't force any trades, and it would give us two bishops against two knights in an open position @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Nxd5 Qxd5
{ 17...Bxd5?!  temporarily keeps the queens on the board, but it doesn't help Black after  18.O-O  ⩲ }
18. Qxd5 Bxd5 19. f3
{ This position was played by Ponomariov and he won a very instructive game. This is a practical endgame where only White can push for a win. It's very difficult to play as Black when you have no practical chances of winning: 1-0 @@StartBracket@@54@@EndBracket@@ Ponomariov,R @@StartBracket@@2631@@EndBracket@@-Gonda,L @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ Czech Republic 2021.   19.O-O  ⩲ The endgame is better for White anyway, but I prefer  19.f3  because of the proximity of the Kf2 to the center. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@67@@EndBracket@@ Deac,B @@StartBracket@@2679@@EndBracket@@ -Demchenko,A @@StartBracket@@2654@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2022 }
