[Black "8.Be3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5
{ Without a doubt, this is the most played move against the Scotch. Many players choose this move to avoid the deep and dangerous theory of the  4...Nf6  variation, as they feel  4...Bc5  is more solid and comfortable to play as Black. }
5. Nb3
{ The most aggressive reply to 4...Bc5 and the best way to continue. We are going to castle long in most cases, making this a very exciting line. }
5... Bb6
{ The main line and Black's most testing move. The black bishop sits on a good diagonal, so it makes sense for Black to keep it there. }
6. Nc3
{ Developing the knight, but this is also a sort of waiting move. The idea is that after  6...Nge7  or  6...Nf6  we will play  7.Bg5  . Meanwhile, if  @@StartFEN@@r1bqk1nr/pppp1ppp/1bn5/8/4P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 4 6@@EndFEN@@  6...d6  happens, we will go for  7.Qe2  and then  --  8.Be3  . }
6... d6
{ An important moment - Black playing ...d6 means that they won't go for ...d5 anytime soon, since it would be a loss of tempo. This is why we play Qe2 against this move, while we don't play that way against 6...Nge7 and 6...Nf6. }
7. Qe2
{ The idea of this line is to castle long. White doesn't need to develop the f1-bishop because there is no good square to put that bishop yet. After long castling we will play for f3-g4 and create an attack on the kingside. Black's attack is slower than White's, so Black's main plan is trying to break in the center with ...d5. }
7... a5 8. Be3
{ My favorite move because it's simple, and White is playing for only two results. }
8... a4
{ Any other move will make Black's previous ...a5 look useless, so it's important for Black to make this move now. The idea is to force our knight back to d2 and also to play ...a3. }
9. Bxb6 axb3
{ The only move, of course. Black doesn't want to get doubled b-pawns and have nothing in return. }
10. Be3 { The only move. } 10... bxa2 11. Rxa2
{ Let's get the pawn back. Now we're playing with the bishop pair. } 11... Rxa2
12. Nxa2 { Notice that Black is not able to play ... d5 easily. } 12... Nge7
13. Nc3
{ 13.Qd2!?  is also possible and it was played by Duda, but it allows  13...d5  . If  13...O-O  14.Nc3  we transpose back to our mainline, but there's no reason to give Black the extra possibility of playing 13...d5.I still recommend everybody to look into the Duda game, because it's a beautiful endgame in which Duda shows a lot of technical skills, proving why the bishop pair is such a big deal. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@25@@EndBracket@@ Duda,J @@StartBracket@@2671@@EndBracket@@ -Hovhannisyan,R @@StartBracket@@2640@@EndBracket@@ Martuni 2016 }
13... O-O 14. Qd2
{ Again, we focus on development and controlling the ...d5 counterplay at the same time. }
14... f5 15. f3
{ I had this position in the World Rapid Championship against Artemiev, but I couldn't find this key move during the game. I instead played  15.Bc4+  , which looked like a decent tempo move, but it was not enough to get an advantage. The main idea of  15.f3!  is to give the Bishop on e3 a hiding place on f2. If you look up my game against Artemiev, you will notice that he managed to trade his Knight for my e3-bishop, which equalizes the game.   15.Bc4+?  ½- @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ ½ @@StartBracket@@38@@EndBracket@@ Corrales Jimenez,F  @@StartBracket@@2530@@EndBracket@@-Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2700@@EndBracket@@ Warsaw 2021 }
15... fxe4 16. Nxe4 { Now if Black plays ...Nf5, we can answer Bf2! } 16... Be6
{ Taking away the best square we could develop the f1-bishop to. } 17. Be2 Nf5
18. Bf2
{ In my game against Artemiev I couldn't keep the e3-bishop and so the position was equal. Here, however, White has the f2-square for the bishop, which is the main reason we've played 15.f3. We keep the bishop pair, securing an advantage for White. }
