[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb6 6.Nc3 d6 - 7.Qe2! Nf6"]
[Black "7...Nge7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qe2 Nge7
{ The main idea of playing this move over  7...Nf6  is to have the option of playing ...f5, which Black doesn't get when the knight is on f6. This could be helpful to Black, because if White's e4-pawn is traded for black's f-pawn, then Black's important ...d5 advance would be easier to carry out. }
8. Be3
{ We continue with our main plan and stop Black from playing ... a5 in the near future, as it would allow us to double their pawns on the b-file, crippling their pawn structure. }
8... O-O { Black will first have to castle short. } 9. O-O-O f5
{ Any other move does not make sense. The e7-knight is strangely positioned, so Black needs to show why the knight was developed this way. If Black decides to play  9...Ng6  instead, White can just reply  10.f4  and keep the knight out of the game. }
10. f4
{ A key step to building the correct pawn structure against the ...f5 break! White wants to create a fortress with the pawn structure h2-g3-f4, preventing Black's knights from jumping to e5, and blockading any potential activity from Black's rook along the f-file. }
10... fxe4
{ Black needs to take. Otherwise, what's the point of ...f5? Black needs to be able to access the f5-square for their knight and bishop. }
11. g3
{ We are not in a rush to retake the pawn. White prioritizes development and coordination, because the e4-pawn is regained in the long-term anyway. Even if Black plays ...d5, we can still take on e4 thanks to the pin on the d-file. }
11... Bxe3+ 12. Qxe3
{ Now White has opened up the f1-a6 diagonal for the f1-bishop, giving us the move Bc4+ that we didn't have earlier. Black, on the other hand, can jump with the knight to f5 or place the bishop on f5. Both moves don't help Black adequately defend the e4-pawn, so White has accomplished the control we needed to get an advantage and at the same time keep the material balance. }
12... d5
{ This move is bad because, again, it doesn't really protect the e4-pawn. } 13.
Bc4
{ Now Black has given us a new weakness to target on d5. We use the pin on the d-file to increase the pressure on this pawn. }
13... Be6 { The only move to protect the pawn. } 14. Nc5 Bf7
{ The only move to not to lose the game immediately. } 15. Nxd5
{ Just a nice tactical finish! } 15... Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Bxd5 17. c4
{ The piece is regained and then the e4-pawn should fall next. White is practically winning! }
