11... Bxe3+ 12. Qxe3
{ Now White has opened up the f1-a6 diagonal for the f1-bishop, giving us the move Bc4+ that we didn't have earlier. Black, on the other hand, can jump with the knight to f5 or place the bishop on f5. Both moves don't help Black adequately defend the e4-pawn, so White has accomplished the control we needed to get an advantage and at the same time keep the material balance. }
12... Nf5 13. Qxe4
{ White intends to play Bc4 followed by Rhe1 with a very easy game. } 13... Re8
{ Targeting e3 and getting a tempo on White's queen. This is Black's best move by far. }
14. Qd5+
{ A gorgeous move which introduces some tactical ideas. We would like to provoke ...Be6 when we can retreat the queen to f3, after which Black can't play ...Ne3 anymore.   14.Qf3?!  is an inaccuracy because it allows the strong move  14...Ne3!  . This was played in a few games in the database, even though White ended up winning two out of those three games. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@62@@EndBracket@@ Iljiushenok,I @@StartBracket@@2532@@EndBracket@@ -Pogosyan,S @@StartBracket@@2455@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk 2019 }
14... Kh8 { 14...Be6?  15.Qf3!  is clearly better for White, as explained. }
15. Qd2
{ The easiest way, but not the only reply.   15.Bd3!?  Nb4   15...Ne3?  16.Qh5!  +-  16.Qf3⩲  White has a target on b7 and Black is not fully developed yet. It's important to notice that White's play is very simple with Rhe1 or g4 at some point. White just needs to avoid Black's silly tricks. }
15... Ne3
{ Black is afraid of the simple Bd3, in which case the f5-knight will be kicked from its outpost with g4. At that point the knight would have to retreat to an awkward square. }
16. Re1 Nxf1
{ This is practically forced because there is no sense in going back with the knight. }
17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. Rxf1
{ After a few forcing moves, all of Black's threats have been stopped and now White is ready to take over the e-file and place a strong knight on d5. A move like Nd4 is also good at some point. }
