[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb6 6.Nc3 d6 - 7.Qe2! Nf6"]
[Black "7...Nf6 with 8...Be6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qe2 Nf6 8.
Be3
{ In this position Black has two ways of continuing - short castling or preparing long castling. In both cases, the space provided by the pawn on e4 in comparison to the pawn on d6 gives White the edge. This is, of course, as long as we don't let Black carry out the ...d5 advance.   8.Bg5!?  is also good and can transpose to the 6...Nf6 7. Bg5 line. }
8... Be6 9. O-O-O
{ We continue with our main plan.   9.g3!?  is an interesting idea that could be used in combination with short castling. The bishop will control d5 from g2, a valuable asset keeping control over the center and preventing Black from exerting pressure. }
9... Qe7 10. g3
{ An amazing idea that's simple and logical at the same time. White is now ready to develop the f1-bishop. Since there was no clear way to do so on the f1-a6 diagonal, we find another way. As mentioned before, on g2 the bishop defends the e4-pawn and helps prevent Black's intended ...d5 advance. This will become even more clear after Black castles long. }
10... O-O-O 11. Bg2
{ With comfortable play for White. We keep our space advantage and have fully coordinated our pieces. We can follow up with a move like Rhe1. As long as we keep an eye on d5 we should keep a long-term advantage. }
*

