[Black "7...Nf6 with 8...O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qe2 Nf6 8.
Be3
{ In this position Black has two ways of continuing - short castling or preparing long castling. In both cases, the space provided by the pawn on e4 in comparison to the pawn on d6 gives White the edge. This is, of course, as long as we don't let Black carry out the ...d5 advance.   8.Bg5!?  is also good and can transpose to the 6...Nf6 7. Bg5 line. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ One of the nice things of Black's early ...d6 is that Black will need to spend a lot more time to prepare the ...d5 break. Another immediate problem for Black is that they can't start a direct attack with ...a5, because White will take on b6, giving Black weak doubled b-pawns as well as a weakness on d6. }
9... Bxe3+ { This helps White's pieces coordinate. } 10. Qxe3
{ Now we are ready to develop the f1-bishop if we can find a good moment. }
10... a5 11. a3
{ A prophylactic move, making sure that Black won't be able to push the pawn to a3 after playing ...a4. Notice that it's very difficult for Black to continue their attack by advancing the b-pawn as well. White's position after  11...a4  12.Nd4  is simply a lot easier to play. }
