1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qe2 Nf6 8.
Be3
{ In this position Black has two ways of continuing - short castling or preparing long castling. In both cases, the space provided by the pawn on e4 in comparison to the pawn on d6 gives White the edge. This is, of course, as long as we don't let Black carry out the ...d5 advance.   8.Bg5!?  is also good and can transpose to the 6...Nf6 7. Bg5 line. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ One of the nice things of Black's early ...d6 is that Black will need to spend a lot more time to prepare the ...d5 break. Another immediate problem for Black is that they can't start a direct attack with ...a5, because White will take on b6, giving Black weak doubled b-pawns as well as a weakness on d6. }
9... Be6 10. f3
{ We continue with our simple plan of attack. We still need to keep track of what happens after Black's ...d5, though. }
10... Re8
{ Many times this is an instinctive move for Black players, but in my opinion it's a waste of time and only gives White an extra tempo. Black has no way to put pressure on e4 when there is a pawn on f3. }
11. Kb1
{ A move that's always important. There are many tactics here that could end with a ...Qg5+ by Black, so let's deal with this potential check right away. }
11... Nd7
{ 11...d5  12.Bg5!  ±  transposes to the mainline of this chapter. Black will eventually lose the d-pawn or struggles with a lack of space for the rest of the game. }
12. g4 a5 13. a3
{ 13.a4!?  White won one of my favorite games with this move. I prefer the a3 approach vs a5 and it's the one I recommend throughout the course. A potential downside of a4 is that it gives Black the b4-square  for their knights. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@37@@EndBracket@@ Areshchenko,A @@StartBracket@@2677@@EndBracket@@-Fedorchuk,S @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ Lvov 2015 }
13... a4 14. Nd2
{ You will notice in this chapter how similar the placement of White's pieces is in many lines. Often there are transpositions between different lines. }
14... Qh4 15. Rg1
{ Stopping ...d5 and lending the g4-pawn some extra protection, which makes the f4 advance possible. }
15... Nd4 { 15...d5?  16.exd5  The bishop is trapped. } 16. Qg2
{ Once again, we don't take on d4. Instead we move our queen and keep the Bishop on e3. }
16... Nxc2 17. Bxb6 Nxa3+ 18. bxa3 Nxb6 19. g5
{ Black's initiative is not enough to compensate for being down a knight. } *

