[Black "7...Nf6 with 8...O-O #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qe2 Nf6 8.
Be3
{ In this position Black has two ways of continuing - short castling or preparing long castling. In both cases, the space provided by the pawn on e4 in comparison to the pawn on d6 gives White the edge. This is, of course, as long as we don't let Black carry out the ...d5 advance.   8.Bg5!?  is also good and can transpose to the 6...Nf6 7. Bg5 line. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ One of the nice things of Black's early ...d6 is that Black will need to spend a lot more time to prepare the ...d5 break. Another immediate problem for Black is that they can't start a direct attack with ...a5, because White will take on b6, giving Black weak doubled b-pawns as well as a weakness on d6. }
9... Be6 10. f3
{ We continue with our simple plan of attack. We still need to keep track of what happens after Black's ...d5, though. }
10... Nd7 { Protecting the bishop on b6 and getting ready to play ...a5. } 11.
g4
{ White has castled and has full control of the center, so it's time to start our typical attack on the kingside. This position reminds me of the English attack in the Sicilian. }
11... a5 12. a3
{ Stopping any of the ideas with a4-a3. Now playing ...a4 is a delicate move for Black, since a4 will be targeted by the c3-knight while Black can't create a weakness on our queenside with ...a3.   12.a4!?  ⩲  is also good, completely stopping ...a4 and giving White a small edge. I prefer not to weaken the b4-square, though. }
12... Nce5 { 12...a4  13.Nd4!  with a small, typical edge. } 13. Nd2
{ Stopping ...Bc4 and ...Nc4 ideas. From d2 the knight also protects the f3-pawn in advance, in case Black plays ...Qf6. }
13... Ng6
{ Black is trying to control the f4- and e5-squares so that their knights will be well-placed after the exchange of dark-squared bishops. }
14. h4
{ Since we have everything under control, we continue with the attack. It might look like Black can grab the h4-pawn, but after  14...Nxh4?  15.g5!  Ng6  16.Qh2  Black immediately loses. }
14... Qf6 { This is an attempt to control the f4- and e5-squares. } 15. g5 Qe5
16. Kb1
{ This move is always good when you don't know what to do. White's position is clearly and visibly better. Black's attack is very slow and with no clear future. White's attack, on the other hand, is already well underway. In this specific position White doesn't want to trade queens, so Kb1 is played to avoid a possible ...Qf4 threat after the exchange of bishops. }
