[Black "7...Nf6 with 8...O-O #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 d6 7. Qe2 Nf6 8.
Be3
{ In this position Black has two ways of continuing - short castling or preparing long castling. In both cases, the space provided by the pawn on e4 in comparison to the pawn on d6 gives White the edge. This is, of course, as long as we don't let Black carry out the ...d5 advance.   8.Bg5!?  is also good and can transpose to the 6...Nf6 7. Bg5 line. }
8... O-O 9. O-O-O
{ One of the nice things of Black's early ...d6 is that Black will need to spend a lot more time to prepare the ...d5 break. Another immediate problem for Black is that they can't start a direct attack with ...a5, because White will take on b6, giving Black weak doubled b-pawns as well as a weakness on d6. }
9... Be6 10. f3
{ We continue with our simple plan of attack. We still need to keep track of what happens after Black's ...d5, though. }
10... d5
{ The pin created by the white rook is quite powerful, so Black is not really threatening anything right now. }
11. Kb1
{ Now White threatens to take on d5, winning a piece.   11.exd5? =  This line is important to understand the reason behind 11.Kb1 and other Kb1 moves in general.  11...Nxd5  12.Nxd5  Bxd5  13.Bxb6  axb6  14.c4  After a forcing line it might seem that White wins a piece, but...  14...Qg5+!  After this move Black escapes and gets the better position. This resource can be prevented by pre-emptively moving the king to b1. }
11... Qd6 12. Bg5
{ Threatening to exchange a defender of the pawn on d5.   12.exd5? =  is not good yet, as after  12...Nxd5  13.Nxd5  Bxd5  14.Bxb6  axb6=  Black equalizes fully because there is no  15.c4  due to  15...Bxc4!  . }
12... d4
{ This advance is now forced, as there is no other way to deal with the threat of Bxf6 followed by Nxd5. }
13. Nb5 Qe5 14. Qd2
{ Protecting the bishop on g5 and attacking d4. This move also prepares the powerful Bf4 skewer. }
14... Bxb3 15. cxb3
{ Just like in the mainline, we take with the c-pawn. White has the bishop pair and has targets on c7 and d4. Also, Black's attack is fully stopped, while ours hasn't even started yet.It should be said that many times in the Scotch we can switch from attacking play to positional play if Black's weaknesses justify it. This could be an example of such a position. In other words, it might not be necessary for us to play g4, h4, etc. }
