{ One of the nice things of Black's early ...d6 is that Black will need to spend a lot more time to prepare the ...d5 break. Another immediate problem for Black is that they can't start a direct attack with ...a5, because White will take on b6, giving Black weak doubled b-pawns as well as a weakness on d6. }
9... Be6 10. f3
{ We continue with our simple plan of attack. We still need to keep track of what happens after Black's ...d5, though. }
10... d5
{ The pin created by the white rook is quite powerful, so Black is not really threatening anything right now. }
11. Kb1
{ Now White threatens to take on d5, winning a piece.   11.exd5? =  This line is important to understand the reason behind 11.Kb1 and other Kb1 moves in general.  11...Nxd5  12.Nxd5  Bxd5  13.Bxb6  axb6  14.c4  After a forcing line it might seem that White wins a piece, but...  14...Qg5+!  After this move Black escapes and gets the better position. This resource can be prevented by pre-emptively moving the king to b1. }
11... Re8 12. Bg5
{ The idea is to put more pressure on d5 by pinning and potentially exchanging the f6-knight. }
12... d4 13. Na4
{ An awesome move! We intend to remove one of the defenders of the pawn on d4. }
13... Qd6 14. Qd2 Bxb3 15. cxb3
{ This recapture might come as a surprise, but you will get used to seeing it in this type of Scotch position. The main long-term idea is that whenever White takes on b6, it is important to not give Black a fully open a-file. Instead, we would like to keep our pawn on a2 so that in case Black tries to attack on the a-file, we can counter by playing a2-a3, blocking the attack. }
