[White "12) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb6 6.Nc3 - 6th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "6...a5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 a5
{ This is a typical move in this variation, but it's not good in this exact position. }
7. Nd5
{ Targeting the b6-bishop with gain of tempo. If Black allows Nxb6 and the doubling of their pawns, our advantage becomes visible right away.   7.Bb5!?  is another interesting approach, stopping ...a4. }
7... a4
{ Black continues with their original idea. It doesn't mean that their idea is good, but there is no good alternative at this point. }
8. Nxb6
{ The obvious reply. Let's take the bishop pair and destroy Black's pawn structure. }
8... cxb6 9. Nd2
{ A little bit of a weird move, but there is a clear idea. The knight will go to c4 if Black allows it, and that would be truly devastating.   9.Nd4!?  is also a good move. }
9... d5
{ One of the possible issues of Nd2 is that it allows this move, but even so Black remains considerably worse. }
10. exd5 Qxd5 11. Nc4
{ The knight has found the best way to position itself. It's now targeting b6 and d6 with a powerful initiative for White. }
