[White "12) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb6 6.Nc3 - 6th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "6...Nge7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nge7 7. Bg5
{ This is a better version than we get after 6...Nf6 because we don't have to worry about the annoying tactic ...Nxe4! This means we can continue to develop with Qd2 and coordinate our forces more easily. The knight on e7 also blocks the e-file for Black's rook. }
7... f6
{ A bit of a waste of time. If Black is attempting to get in ...f5, then why play ...f6 here? }
8. Bh4 O-O 9. Qd2
{ Our typical way of setting up, preparing long castling. I got to test out this move in a recent blitz game. }
9... a5
{ This is one of the most typical and most annoying moves Black can play in these lines. }
10. a4
{ A logical response! Stopping Black from playing ...a4 all together. The downside is that we give away the b4-square for the c6-knight. The good news is that even with a black knight on b4, there is nothing to worry about. }
10... d6
{ Too slow!   10...d5!?  is probably Black's best shot! After  11.exd5  Nb4  12.O-O-O  White defends the pawn, and after  12...Bf5  13.Na1!!  it's not clear if Black has enough initiative for being down a pawn. White's knight on a1 is temporarily there until we can develop the f1-bishop and place the h1-rook on e1. }
11. O-O-O
{ ⩲, as in the game Corrales Jimenez,F @@StartBracket@@2545@@EndBracket@@-Quesada Perez,L @@StartBracket@@2567@@EndBracket@@ Medellin 2024. }
11... Be6 12. f4
{ White's initiative and extra space in the center are very clear. Black's attack on the queenside is completely blocked by the a4-pawn, making it very dificult for Black to create something at all. Most of the time in this type of position, the most important thing is to stop Black from playing the equalizer ...d5! }
