[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb6 6.Nc3 - 6th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "6...Nf6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6
{ With this move Black tries to quickly castle short and play ...d5. This is not something we should take lightly, and that's why Bg5 is the best move here. }
7. Bg5
{ Now, generally speaking, there are two ways of playing this position as Black. The first and most popular way is to castle short, and the second way is to castle long. In both cases Black will have to play the moves ...h6 and ...g5 to get rid of the annoying pin on the f6-knight. }
7... O-O
{ Black first castles and will then attempt to play ...h6, ...g5 and ...d5. Black can still transpose into 7...h6 variations, but Black cannot delay the move ...h6 for much longer and that's something to keep in mind. }
8. Qe2
{ The best way to deal with the ...d5 break is to be ready to pin the pawn with O-O-O. Also, as Black has already castled short, we take advantage of this fact by preparing to go the opposite way, making the position more dynamic.   8.Nd5??  would be a huge blunder, allowing the beautiful move  8...Bxf2+!  ∓ when  9.Kxf2  is answered by  9...Nxe4+  . }
8... h6 9. Bh4
{ The only move!   9.Be3?  Why did we play Bg5? We need to pin the f6-knight in order to prevent ...d5. It doesn't help us if we remove the bishop from the h4-d8 diagonal - Black can counter immediately with  9...d5! }
9... Nd4 10. Qd3
{ A key idea that we will see often when Qe2 is on the board. We don't want to exchange on d4 because the b6-bishop would become active, targeting our knight on c3, and consequently our e4-pawn would become a weakness. The best move is to leave the d4-knight as it is and just reposition our queen.   10.Qd2?  Be careful! Here  10...Nxe4!  -+ is a cute trick! }
10... Nxb3 11. axb3
{ Next we will castle long. It's not clear if we will try to exchange the b6-bishop for our c3-knight, so there is no reason to worry about a fully open a-file yet. }
11... c6
{ Getting ...d5 in is a necessity for Black, or they will get in trouble. With this move, Black is not only trying to play ...d5 but also stopping the white knight from jumping to d5. }
12. O-O-O
{ We finally castle. White's advantage is visible and Black has not yet played ...d5, nor do they have an attack at all. }
12... Re8 13. Be2 { Continuing our most needed development. } 13... d5
{ Finally Black gets to play ...d5, but it comes with a big downside: they will get a weak isolated pawn. }
14. exd5 cxd5 15. Rhe1
{ Black has no counterplay. A position like this is not very comfortable for Black, because we have a long-term advantage with a static pawn structure. }
