[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb6 6.Nc3 - 6th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "6...Nf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nf6
{ With this move Black tries to quickly castle short and play ...d5. This is not something we should take lightly, and that's why Bg5 is the best move here. }
7. Bg5
{ Now, generally speaking, there are two ways of playing this position as Black. The first and most popular way is to castle short, and the second way is to castle long. In both cases Black will have to play the moves ...h6 and ...g5 to get rid of the annoying pin on the f6-knight. }
7... h6
{ Immediately questioning the g5-bishop and intending to follow up with ...g5 after Bh4. }
8. Bh4 d6
{ This is a very interesting move order because Black wants to keep their options open when it comes to castling. The only downside of this move is that now playing for a quick ...d5 is out of the question. At the same time, White has many ways of playing that are good, so it's hard for Black to get a good position against all of White's options. }
9. Bd3
{ The point is that Black cannot play ...d5 anymore, and now a boring line where White castles short is enough for us to get an advantage. Black will need to play ...g5 or maneuver the c6-knight to g6 to get rid of the pin on the f6-knight, which is uncomfortable either way. It's important to play  9.Bd3  only after Black plays ...d6 and practically gives up on the ...d5 break.   9.Qd2??  is a horrible move that allows Black to win a pawn with  9...Nxe4!  ∓  . }
9... O-O
{ Castling so quickly is not the best, as now playing ...g5 would only weaken Black's king. }
10. O-O
{ 10.Qe2!?  ⩲  We can castle either way. White is better thanks to the pin on the f6-knight. }
