[Black "6...Qh4 7.Qe2 Nge7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Qh4
{ A worst version of Qf6 because we can always play g3 and get a free tempo off the queen, then develop the Bf1-g2. }
7. Qe2
{ Just following up with our plans like nothing happened, this way we prove that the Qh4 is useless, in fact is helping us do what we were going to do anyway.   7.g3!?  is also very good!  7...Qf6  8.Qe2⩲  A very similar approach, and it could potentially transpose. }
7... Nge7 8. Be3
{ Let's keep it simple and continue with our plan! Other moves like  8.g3  or  8.a4  are great too! }
8... d6
{ In this position, we can follow up with our idea of O-O-O and g3-Bg2 in which case, we will play for positional space, giving us an easy game. But we have something much more exciting and for that, we would rather not define our king just yet. This is because if things go our way, we will be castling short. }
9. g3 { First, let's get this out of the way! } 9... Qf6
{ The queen's best retreat by far. } 10. Bg2
{ An expected follow-up move that also serves as a waiting move! } 10... Bd7
{ A more flexible move! } 11. Nb5
{ A typical way for targeting c7 and placing the knight in a very active position. This is nice when White doesn't have access to Nd5. It's now very difficult for Black to kick the knight from b5 because if c7-c6 is played, the pawn on d6 will be hanging. }
11... O-O-O 12. Bxb6 { Now Black loses the option of kicking with a6 too! }
12... axb6 { And finally, we can see the reason for delaying castle! } 13. a4
{ With an intense attack, our next move will be 14. a5 where we will obtain a very dangerous open a-file. If Black tries to take the free pawn on b2, things can only get worse! }
13... Qxb2 14. O-O
{ This line is a great example of the flexibility of the Scotch, we were meant to be long castling but suddenly, we created a new idea that was more powerful by short castling. }
