[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Qf6 7. Qe2
{ Following one of the main course ideas of playing Be3 and O-O-O. It's the perfect time to do so since we protect f2 on the way. White is also threatening the strong 8. Nd5! which is devastating for Black. }
7... Nge7 { The best move by far! Stops Nd5 and continue Black's development. }
8. Be3
{ This is a great alternative to continue our regular plan, but Black has the solid approach of castling long. I feel, though, that most people will Immediately short castle, making Black's position extremely difficult. }
8... d6
{ Black's best approach! Trying to follow with ...Bd7 or ...Be6 and ...O-O-O. Escaping from the kingside and the f4 pawn storm.   8...O-O ?  Castling long here is not an option for Black. The Black queen on f6 is a target that White can now use to accelerate the pawn expansion on the kingside.  9.O-O-O !  With simple play, the strong Yu Yangyi won a very easy game.  9...d6  10.Kb1±  Yu-Pourkashiyan, Jakarta 2011. }
9. O-O-O { We now continue with our ways! } 9... Be6
{ This move is dangerously natural, but already a big inaccuracy. White has a great tactical resource! }
10. Nd5 Bxd5 { Only move to not get a lost position right away! } 11. exd5 Ne5
12. f4
{ And the key move to prove our point! Now Black knights are completely useless since they need to find squares that are not very active. After  12...Nd7  13.g4±  we will continue with g5 followed by Bh3 and Qd3-b5.   After  12...N5g6?!  13.g3!±  We are basically playing against the activity of the knights to prove that our minor pieces are better than Black's minor pieces. }
