[Black "6...Qf6 7.Qe2 Nge7 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Qf6 7. Qe2
{ Following one of the main course ideas of playing Be3 and O-O-O. It's the perfect time to do so since we protect f2 on the way. White is also threatening the strong 8. Nd5! which is devastating for Black. }
7... Nge7 { The best move by far! Stops Nd5 and continue Black's development. }
8. h4
{ Here we play another outstanding move! We are constantly looking for ways to play h4 in this course, and that's why I am picking this line. Having the queen placed on f6 can only make h4 even more logical. We now threaten tempi with Bg5 and the other typical h4 ideas, like Rh3 or h5-h6. }
8... d6 9. Bg5
{ Now, thanks to h4, White is a bit faster with development, making h4 more appealing. We can always go back to e3 if Black decides to kick the Bg5 with h6, but it's nice that we get a free tempo off the Black queen. }
9... Qe6 10. O-O-O { The most common approach is good too. } 10... Bd7
{ 10...h6?!  11.Be3⩲  Hakobyan-Swiercz, Saint Louis 2023.   10...f6  11.Be3⩲ }
11. g3
{ An improvement to Shankland’s play. The f1-h3 diagonal is a lot more active for the f1 bishop making this development a lot more exciting.   11.Qd2!?  Shankland-Rapport, Saint Louis 2021.   11.h5!?  h6  12.Bxe7!  Nxe7  13.g3⩲ }
11... O-O-O
{ 11...f6  Anytime our bishop is kicked we simply return to e3, sometimes we might go to f4. Here, though, we have a much stronger desperado!  12.Bh3!  ↑ }
12. Bh3
{ It already looks scary for the black queen! Luckily, Black has a strong move! }
12... f5 13. Rhe1
{ The position is complicated, but I like White's chances better because White's pieces feel more active. Black's play has to be very accurate not to get a worse position quickly. }
