[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb6 6.Nc3 - 6th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "6...Qf6 7.Qe2 Nge7 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Qf6 7. Qe2
{ Following one of the main course ideas of playing Be3 and O-O-O. It's the perfect time to do so since we protect f2 on the way. White is also threatening the strong 8. Nd5! which is devastating for Black. }
7... Nge7 { The best move by far! Stops Nd5 and continue Black's development. }
8. h4
{ Here we play another outstanding move! We are constantly looking for ways to play h4 in this course, and that's why I am picking this line. Having the queen placed on f6 can only make h4 even more logical. We now threaten tempi with Bg5 and the other typical h4 ideas, like Rh3 or h5-h6. }
8... d6 9. Bg5
{ Now, thanks to h4, White is a bit faster with development, making h4 more appealing. We can always go back to e3 if Black decides to kick the Bg5 with h6, but it's nice that we get a free tempo off the Black queen. }
9... Qe6 10. a4
{ A very difficult move to understand yet but the most precise one! Played by Praggnanandha in a recent rapid game has the fantastic idea of forcing Black to play ...a6 or ...a5 to stop the bishop from practically getting trapped. After the black a-pawn moves, the Nd5! jump becomes a practically winning threat because of the Nxb6 follow up, in which case Black will be forced to take with the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@not the a-pawn anymore@@EndBracket@@ and so destroying Black's pawn structure.Another important idea is that if we ever need to retreat, Bg5- e3 the Bb6 will be forced to take back on e3, which helps activate our queen. }
10... a6
{ 10...f6  11.Bd2!  Not yet Be3, we want Black to create a weakness first.  11...a6  12.h5!  ↑   12.Nd5!?  ⩲   10...a5?  11.Nb5!  ± Now after  12.Be3  the c7-pawn will be a huge target! }
11. O-O-O Bd7
{ Black again tries to castle long and there is no faster way of doing so. }
12. Qd2
{ Now 13. Nd5 is a very serious threat! If we remove the a4 and a6 moves from this position, then it wouldn't be as bad for Black. }
12... f6 { 12...O-O-O ?  A simple move but a massive blunder.  13.Nd5+- } 13.
Bf4
{ Still giving more power to Nd5, We want to be able to target the bishop on b6 with the knight! }
13... Qf7 { 13...O-O-O ?  14.Nd5± } 14. h5
{ A waiting move this far in the opening, we are officially waiting for O-O-O so we can play Nd5 with more power. }
14... O-O-O
{ 14...O-O  15.h6!  ± Now  h5  is no longer a waiting move but a useful one! }
15. Nd5 Nxd5 { A forced trade.  15...Ba7??  16.Nxc7+- } 16. exd5 Ne5 17. Be3
{ A huge move! We can finally give Be3 some use! Now we threaten Bxb6 and f4, giving Black a ton of trouble. }
