{ Following one of the main course ideas of playing Be3 and O-O-O. It's the perfect time to do so since we protect f2 on the way. White is also threatening the strong 8. Nd5! which is devastating for Black. }
7... Nge7 { The best move by far! Stops Nd5 and continue Black's development. }
8. h4
{ Here we play another outstanding move! We are constantly looking for ways to play h4 in this course, and that's why I am picking this line. Having the queen placed on f6 can only make h4 even more logical. We now threaten tempi with Bg5 and the other typical h4 ideas, like Rh3 or h5-h6. }
8... d6 9. Bg5
{ Now, thanks to h4, White is a bit faster with development, making h4 more appealing. We can always go back to e3 if Black decides to kick the Bg5 with h6, but it's nice that we get a free tempo off the Black queen. }
9... Qe6 10. a4
{ A very difficult move to understand yet but the most precise one! Played by Praggnanandha in a recent rapid game has the fantastic idea of forcing Black to play ...a6 or ...a5 to stop the bishop from practically getting trapped. After the black a-pawn moves, the Nd5! jump becomes a practically winning threat because of the Nxb6 follow up, in which case Black will be forced to take with the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@not the a-pawn anymore@@EndBracket@@ and so destroying Black's pawn structure.Another important idea is that if we ever need to retreat, Bg5- e3 the Bb6 will be forced to take back on e3, which helps activate our queen. }
10... a6
{ 10...f6  11.Bd2!  Not yet Be3, we want Black to create a weakness first.  11...a6  12.h5!  ↑   12.Nd5!?  ⩲   10...a5?  11.Nb5!  ± Now after  12.Be3  the c7-pawn will be a huge target! }
11. O-O-O f6 12. Be3
{ Now Black is force to take on e3, which is perfect for our coordination. }
12... Bxe3+ 13. Qxe3 Bd7
{ Black keeps the long castle option open to avoid the opposite castle type of position.   13...O-O  14.Nd4!  ⩲ }
14. Nd4
{ A simple improvement to Pragg's game. It's very typical in the 4....Bc5 5. Nb3 Scotch to bring the b3 knight back to the center once we finished coordinating. The general idea is to trade a knight that's not very active for a more centralized black knight.   14.Kb1  Praggnanandhaa-Vidit, London 2024. }
14... Nxd4 15. Rxd4
{ We now have plenty of ways to continue, but some ideas are 16. Bc4, Kb1, h5-h6 and the possibility of Nd5. Not including ideas like Qa7. }
15... Nc6
{ This move is an example of how quickly bad the position can get for Black. }
16. Nd5 { A beautiful desperado, targeting c7; Black is in big pressure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb4+"]
[Black "Alternative 6.Bd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb4+
{ This is a good alternative to  5...Bb6  for Black. They intend to stop us from being able to develop the b1-knight to c3. This is an unusual line that's been played by some of the best players in the world, so it's worth studying in some depth. }
6. Bd2
{ This is another logical move that's good too. The idea is to keep the c3-square available for the knight. }
6... a5
{ If Black takes on d2 we want to recapture with the queen so we are still able to develop our queenside knight to c3. }
7. a3 { Defining the bishop's future as quickly as possible. } 7... Be7 8. Be3
{ Giving the b3-knight the d4 and d2-squares if needed.   8.Nc3?!  a4!  9.Nc1∞  1-0 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Corrales Jimenez,F @@StartBracket@@2525@@EndBracket@@ -Williams,J @@StartBracket@@2425@@EndBracket@@ Chesterfield 2022 }
8... a4 9. Nd4 { Now you see why we played Be3 on the previous move. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 4...Bc5 5.Nb3 Bb4+"]
[Black "7...Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb4+
{ This is a good alternative to  5...Bb6  for Black. They intend to stop us from being able to develop the b1-knight to c3. This is an unusual line that's been played by some of the best players in the world, so it's worth studying in some depth. }
6. c3
{ This is my favorite reply. Yes, we are blocking the c3-square for our knight, but Black's bishop has to retreat to a passive square in exchange. }
6... Be7
{ An obvious downside to the 5...Bb4+ move for Black is the placement of the Bishop on e7, where it is not as active as it would have been on b6. }
7. f4
{ There is no time to waste! Let's grab space and exploit the fact that the black bishop is not on b6 anymore. This move also gives us the possibility of playing e5, and this could be very annoying for the knight on g8.Another idea is to prepare for ...d5 by being able to play e5. The f4-pawn protects our e-pawn in case of a future e5, so now Black will struggle to get the freeing move ...d5 played.   7.Bd3?  would be a classic mistake, giving away any hope for an opening advantage.  7...d5!  This is why! Allowing ...d5 is no good and so Black equalizes on the spot. }
7... Nf6
{ This allows e5, which forces the knight to go back to g8 with a slight advantage for White. }
8. Bd3
{ This move could transpose to the mainline, and it's the strongest move. The idea is that we only want to play e5 once Black has played ...d5. That way Black cannot attack the e5-pawn with ...d6 anymore. We will see more of this in the coming variations.   8.e5!?  ⩲ }
8... d6 9. N1d2 { tranposes to the mainline with 7...d6. } *

