[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb4+
{ This is a good alternative to  5...Bb6  for Black. They intend to stop us from being able to develop the b1-knight to c3. This is an unusual line that's been played by some of the best players in the world, so it's worth studying in some depth. }
6. c3
{ This is my favorite reply. Yes, we are blocking the c3-square for our knight, but Black's bishop has to retreat to a passive square in exchange. }
6... Be7
{ An obvious downside to the 5...Bb4+ move for Black is the placement of the Bishop on e7, where it is not as active as it would have been on b6. }
7. f4
{ There is no time to waste! Let's grab space and exploit the fact that the black bishop is not on b6 anymore. This move also gives us the possibility of playing e5, and this could be very annoying for the knight on g8.Another idea is to prepare for ...d5 by being able to play e5. The f4-pawn protects our e-pawn in case of a future e5, so now Black will struggle to get the freeing move ...d5 played.   7.Bd3?  would be a classic mistake, giving away any hope for an opening advantage.  7...d5!  This is why! Allowing ...d5 is no good and so Black equalizes on the spot. }
7... d6
{ This is necessary to prevent us from playing e5, kicking Black's knight once it comes to f6. Without this move there would be no easy way for Black to develop. }
8. Bd3
{ Since Black has played ...d6 we don't care about ...d5 anymore. The bishop is placed perfectly on d3, pointing at h7 and protecting the e4-pawn. If Black plays ...d5 now or in the immediate future, we should immediately answer e5. }
8... d5
{ Black plays ...d5 after having played ...d6. It's a bit strange but the idea is that the g8-knight is not on f6 yet, so White doesn't gain a tempo with e5 and Black can develop the knight in a different way. }
9. e5 Nh6 10. O-O { 10.N1d2!? } 10... O-O
{ Black tries to be as flexible as possible and wants to break with ...f6 soon. }
11. Qc2
{ Targeting h7 and provoking an unwanted weakening of the kingside.   11.N1d2!?  ⩲ }
11... g6 12. Na3
{ This knight will get into play via b5 and d4.   12.N1d2!?  ⩲  The idea is to transport the knight to f3.  12...Bf5?!  13.Nf3± }
12... Bf5
{ 12...Bxa3?  13.bxa3↑  leaves Black with enormous holes on the dark squares on their kingside. }
13. Nb5
{ Next we will put this knight on d4. It's still not clear what Black is doing with the h6-knight. }
