12... dxe5 13. fxe5 Ng4 14. Bf4
{ The best move no doubt. White keeps the pressure and finishes their development. Black, on the other hand, is struggling to find counterplay. Note that Black cannot grab the e5-pawn:  14...Ngxe5??  loses right away to a trick we've seen before.  15.Nxe5  Nxe5  16.Bxe5  Rxe5  17.Bxh7++-   14.Bxh7+?!  ⩲  My game continued this way and I managed to win a pawn with this move, but Black's compensation was clear and the game became very difficult for White. It was a blitz game, so I opted to go for the more fun line, but objectively this move was worse.  14...Kxh7  Not taking the bishop is not possible here for Black. At this point it looks like White just blundered a bishop, but of course it was all calculated beforehand.  15.Ng5+  Kg8  The only move!   After  15...Kg6  White answers  16.Qc2+  and Black can simply resign. My opponent showed great resilience and resourcefulness during this game, and because of that he didn't lose right away.  16.Qc2!  f5  Another strong move!  17.exf6  Nxf6  There is nothing else. Black has no other way to stop the mate on h7.  18.Rxf6!  The whole point of the sac on h7. Black is forced to give back the knight to survive.  18...Re1+  19.Rf1  An important detail about this position is that Black has no threats on the a7-g1 diagonal because the b3-knight does a great job defending against any checks on c5.  19...Rxf1+  20.Kxf1⩲  0-1 @@StartBracket@@46@@EndBracket@@ Corrales Jimenez,F @@StartBracket@@2532@@EndBracket@@ -Nguyen,N @@StartBracket@@2641@@EndBracket@@ Chess.com INT 2020. White is a pawn up for now. After a lot of mistakes @@StartBracket@@as is typical of blitz games@@EndBracket@@ I ended up losing the game, but it was good practice for me as it gave me a bigger understanding of this variation and a boost of confidence in a line that I would have likely never studied before. This is one of the main reasons I wanted to include part of this game in the course. }
