[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) 4...Bb4+"]
[Black "7...g6 with 11...Qb4+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3
{ Black's idea is to lure our pawn to c3 so that we can't directly put a knight on c3 anymore. Now, if White wishes to play Nc3, we need to play c4 first. }
5... Bc5 6. Be3 Bb6 7. Nf5
{ The easiest way to play!  7.Qg4  was played by Kasparov and is also interesting, but I like  7.Nf5  better. }
7... g6 8. Bxb6 axb6
{ Opening the a-file, which gives Black some counterplay. } 9. Ne3
{ This is the main point of Nf5. The knight is now placed on its best possible square, controlling f5 and d5. It will be very difficult for Black to achieve any counterplay in the center. }
9... Nf6 10. f3
{ Intending to build a Maroczy bind position. The next move is c4, and then we will play Nc3. As usual in the Scotch, we are fighting to stop the equalizing move ...d5! }
10... Qe7
{ Black tries to trade queens in an attempt to reduce their spatial problems. }
11. c4 Qb4+
{ This is the reason for 10...Qe7. This idea doesn't help Black much, though, as I believe the resulting endgame is just really hard for Black to hold. }
12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2
{ Now that the queens are gone, placing the king in the center is good. } 13...
d6 14. Nc3
{ And White is the only one with winning chances. We have more space and no weaknesses, which means Black will have to suffer for a long time. }
