[White "14) 4...Bb4+"]
[Black "7...g6 with 11...Nh5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3
{ Black's idea is to lure our pawn to c3 so that we can't directly put a knight on c3 anymore. Now, if White wishes to play Nc3, we need to play c4 first. }
5... Bc5 6. Be3 Bb6 7. Nf5
{ The easiest way to play!  7.Qg4  was played by Kasparov and is also interesting, but I like  7.Nf5  better. }
7... g6 8. Bxb6 axb6
{ Opening the a-file, which gives Black some counterplay. } 9. Ne3
{ This is the main point of Nf5. The knight is now placed on its best possible square, controlling f5 and d5. It will be very difficult for Black to achieve any counterplay in the center. }
9... Nf6 10. f3
{ Intending to build a Maroczy bind position. The next move is c4, and then we will play Nc3. As usual in the Scotch, we are fighting to stop the equalizing move ...d5! }
10... O-O 11. c4 Nh5
{ This doesn't threaten much other than ...Qh4+. Black's idea is probably to play ...f5 or ...Nf4 at some point. }
12. Qd2 { Now we can answer ...Qh4+ with Qf2. } 12... d6
{ Black wants to play ...f5 at some point, but that's not as easy as it sounds. }
13. Nc3 f5
{ Here's an example of the fact that the ...f5 advance is not always good. }
14. exf5 gxf5
{ Taking with the g-pawn weakens Black's structure and is not the idea behind the ...f5 advance. If Black doesn't recapture on f5 with a piece, they probably shouldn't play ...f5 in the first place. }
15. O-O-O
{ White wants a situation with opposite side castling, as White's potential attack is much more dangerous than Black's. When a player has more space than their opponent, they usually have much less problems creating a nice attack, and such is the case here! }
