[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3
{ Black's idea is to lure our pawn to c3 so that we can't directly put a knight on c3 anymore. Now, if White wishes to play Nc3, we need to play c4 first. }
5... Bc5 6. Be3 Bb6 7. Nf5
{ The easiest way to play!  7.Qg4  was played by Kasparov and is also interesting, but I like  7.Nf5  better. }
7... g6 8. Bxb6 axb6
{ Opening the a-file, which gives Black some counterplay. } 9. Ne3
{ This is the main point of Nf5. The knight is now placed on its best possible square, controlling f5 and d5. It will be very difficult for Black to achieve any counterplay in the center. }
9... Nf6 10. f3
{ Intending to build a Maroczy bind position. The next move is c4, and then we will play Nc3. As usual in the Scotch, we are fighting to stop the equalizing move ...d5! }
10... O-O 11. c4 d6 12. Nc3
{ You can practically premove Nc3 after having played c4. It's natural and the whole point of White's setup. }
12... Nd7
{ I saw this plan in a game and I thought it was worth taking a quick look at. }
13. Be2 { Another simple move, White prepares to castle kingside. } 13... Nc5
14. O-O
{ The main idea of Black's ... Nc5 plan is to introduce the option of playing ...f5. Since Black wants to free up some space, it makes sense to trade their f-pawn for our e4-pawn.   14.Qd2??  Do not fall for this tactical trick!  14...Nb3-+ }
14... f5 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Qd2
{ And that's it again. Notice how White's moves came very naturally and easy. We will follow up with Rfe1 and Rad1. We'll put one knight on d5 and the other one could come to b5, etc. White's advantage is clear! }
