1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4
{ This is a tricky move that's very popular online. I've played it a couple of times vs Dubov, and it's a must know for all Scotch players. Believe me when I say you will encounter this move! }
5. Nb5
{ The initiative cannot wait! White gives up a pawn for development and immediate pressure on c7. }
5... Qxe4+ 6. Be2
{ Now Black needs to protect c7. This is a tough job as the black queen is not available for the defense anymore. }
6... Bb4+
{ The best way to continue as Black. The idea is to defend c7 with ...Ba5 so that it's not necessary to move the king to d8, keeping Black's castling rights alive. }
7. N1c3
{ 7.Bd2  is also possible. After  7...Kd8  8.O-O  play has actually transposed to the mainline with 5... Bb4+. }
7... Bxc3+
{ This move doesn't solve any problems for Black and it gives up the bishop pair. }
8. bxc3
{ This is forced! We need to keep the threat to c7 alive so we have time to castle on the next move. }
8... Kd8 { The only way to protect c7 now. } 9. O-O
{ And now that the pawn on g2 is protected, the initiative will become more clear as we continue developing and activating pieces. }
9... a6
{ A logical move which Black will have to play at some point, but it's not enough. }
10. Bf3 { With simple play White will get a great amount of pressure. } 10...
Qh4 11. Nd4
{ The f1-rook will go to e1 and the bishop on c1 to f4. Doubling rooks on the e-file is great plan, as well as simply playing Qe2. One thing to avoid as White is the trade of queens. When we are down material and have to keep attacking chances on Black's king, we don't want to trade queens. }
