[Black "Alternative 5.Nb5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4
{ This is a tricky move that's very popular online. I've played it a couple of times vs Dubov, and it's a must know for all Scotch players. Believe me when I say you will encounter this move! }
5. Nb5
{ The initiative cannot wait! White gives up a pawn for development and immediate pressure on c7. }
5... Nf6 6. Nd2
{ 6.Nxc7+!?  is good for White too, but it gives Black some chances and the main move is just very simple and strong. }
6... Kd8
{ The move Black doesn't want to play, but has to. After this move, even if White loses the e-pawn, there will always be sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
7. g3
{ Developing and attacking. Our light-squared bishop will often be better on g2 than on e2. }
7... Qh5
{ Black has no choice but to offer a queen trade in a position where they lack counterplay.   7...Qg4  is similar to 7...Qh5. After  8.Be2  Qh3  we transpose back to 7...Qh5. }
8. Be2
{ As usual, in positions where we have a development advantage and the initiative, we decline to trade queens.   8.Qxh5!?  Nxh5  9.Bg2⩲  also gives White easy play. }
8... Qh3 9. Nf3
{ A sophisticated move that continues to put pressure on Black's development. We don't need to look too far to understand that the position of the king on d8 will provide more than enough compensation for the e4-pawn. }
9... Nxe4 10. Qd3
{ Gaining another tempo, this time on the e4-knight. Next White is castling either kingside or queenside with a strong attacking position. If  10...Qe6  we first play  11.Nfd4!  , and then we castle on either side of the board, depending on where Black's queen goes next. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) 4...Qh4"]
[Black "Alternative 5.Nb5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qh4
{ This is a tricky move that's very popular online. I've played it a couple of times vs Dubov, and it's a must know for all Scotch players. Believe me when I say you will encounter this move! }
5. Nb5
{ The initiative cannot wait! White gives up a pawn for development and immediate pressure on c7. }
5... Bb4+
{ The most precise move order for Black. Check out the lines after 5...Qxe4+ to understand why this statement is true. }
6. Bd2
{ This way we prevent Black's ...Ba5 defensive idea.   6.N1c3?  is the main reason why Black plays 5...Bb4. With the moves ...Qxe4+ and Be2 included, the move Nb1c3 is very strong, but here it is not good due to  6...Ba5!  ⩱ }
6... Qxe4+
{ Black needs to take the pawn. Otherwise there was no point to playing ...Qh4. }
7. Be2
{ We still threaten to take on c7, and we will castle on the next move. } 7...
Kd8
{ This is the whole point of the pawn sacrifice. White has compensation in two ways - Black's king is now stuck in the center and White is ahead in development.   7...Qxg2  8.Bf3+-  is something we've seen before already. Nxc7+ is next. }
8. O-O a6
{ It makes sense for Black to try to kick the knight straight away, but it doesn't work that well. }
9. N1c3
{ White introduces the idea of Nxc7 followed by Nd5+ check. This means Black's queen cannot lose sight of the d5-square. }
9... Bxc3 10. Nxc3
{ The only move, but we get a tempo on Black's queen right away. Our initiative cannot stop, you've got to ride the wave when you are on it! }
10... Qd4 11. Bh5
{ This is just a cool move to provoke a weakness on the kingside. Now Black either gives up the f7-pawn immediately or creates some big holes in their pawn structure. }
*

