{ Black needs to take the pawn. Otherwise there was no point to playing ...Qh4. }
7. Be2
{ We still threaten to take on c7, and we will castle on the next move. } 7...
Kd8
{ This is the whole point of the pawn sacrifice. White has compensation in two ways - Black's king is now stuck in the center and White is ahead in development.   7...Qxg2  8.Bf3+-  is something we've seen before already. Nxc7+ is next. }
8. O-O Bxd2 9. Nxd2 { Speeding up the initiative. The faster the better! } 9...
Qg6 10. Re1
{ A logical move. Rooks should we placed on open or semi-open files. } 10...
Nf6
{ Stopping Bh5.   10...a6?  11.Bh5!  Qh6  12.Nc3±  with ideas of Nd5 and Bxf7. }
11. Bf3
{ Opening the file for the rook and placing the bishop on a great diagonal. }
11... Re8
{ The most logical move in my opinion. Trading is good if you are up a pawn. }
12. Rxe8+ Nxe8 13. Nc4
{ White has a strong initiative that more than compensates for the pawn down. For example  13...a6?  is already a mistake due to  14.Nd4!  . Again, simple play is enough here! All we need to do is to place our rook in the center and our initiative will flow by itself.  14...Nxd4  15.Qxd4  Qf6  Black attempts to trade queens and ease the pain, but of course we're not going to let that happen!  16.Qe3!  ±  And Black can hardly coordinate. The Bf3 points at b7 and the a1-rook is coming into the game next. }
