[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) 4...Qf6"]
[Black "6...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qf6 5. Nb3
{ The best move in my opinion! White makes it impossible for Black to play ...Bc5, which would be a typical continuation for Black after 4...Qf6. Now Black has no decent square to develop the f8-bishop to. White also declines the knight trade, wich helps us keep our space advantage. If you have more space, it's usually better to avoid piece trades, and that's the case here. }
5... Qg6
{ A necessary move for Black to make sense of 4...Qf6 and to give the knight on g8 an important development square on f6. It's also a forcing move that pressures e4 and g2 at the same time. }
6. f3
{ The strongest way to defend e4. A move like  6.Nc3  would allow the annoying pin  6...Bb4  and we definitely don't want to allow Black to develop the f8-bishop actively. }
6... Bd6
{ Black threatens  7.--  Bxh2!  8.Rxh2  Qg3+  , winning the exchange. It's clear, though, that this move cannot be as good as  @@StartFEN@@r1b1kbnr/pppp1ppp/2n3q1/8/4P3/1N3P2/PPP3PP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6...Nf6  because it blocks the development of the Bishop on c8. }
7. g3
{ Stopping the ...Bxh2 idea and making it possible to develop the f1-bishop to g2. We also don't want to disregard a move like f4, in order to increase our space advantage and to get a chance to trap Black's queen. This entire line is relatively new on the top level, and 7.g3 has not been tried at a high level yet.   7.g4!?  was played by Nepo twice and gave him 2 relatively easy wins, but his opponents didn't play the annoying  7...Nge7!  ⩱  0-1 @@StartBracket@@67@@EndBracket@@ Yatzenko,A @@StartBracket@@2354@@EndBracket@@-Puranik,A @@StartBracket@@2548@@EndBracket@@ Kazan 2019. }
7... Nge7
{ 7...Bxg3+?  is just bad, as Black doesn't have enough pieces developed to create issues for our king. There is not enough compensation after  8.hxg3  Qxg3+  9.Ke2+-  . }
8. Bg2 O-O
{ A simple move like this would instantly give White a clear advantage. This proves how difficult the position is for Black and how accurately Black has to play here - one simple or natural move and they are out. }
9. O-O
{ Followed by f4 and Nc3. Black is way behind in development and the black queen will start suffering the consequences of being placed so out in the open. }
9... f5
{ Trying to fight for space with this move is not good enough for Black. White goes on with their plans! }
10. f4
{ A short-term pawn sacrifice to gain space and finish our development. } 10...
fxe4 11. Nc3
{ There is nothing Black can do to stop Nxe4 or Bxe4. White is just clearly better. }
