{ 11.Nc3  Qxf4  12.dxc6  transposes to the line 11.dxc6. } 11... Qxf4 12. Nc3
{ White gives back the pawn, but makes sure Black's pawns will be doubled. There is a saying that says 'having doubled pawns is like being down one pawn', so this is a good idea.   12.cxb7!?  Bxb7  13.N1d2⩲  is also playable if you would like to be up a pawn, but you would have to deal with a stronger initiative coming from Black. }
12... bxc6 13. g3
{ This is no doubt a complex position, that will take some time getting used to. White is a few moves away from full coordination with Bg2-Rhe1 and then Kg1. After White accomplishes this, Black's pawn structure is problematic and the a7-g1 diagonal is controlled by the Nb3 knight. Alternatively, White can also play Kg2 and develop the bishop to d3 or c4. }
