{ A very flexible move! White is waiting for the f8-bishop to move and we get rid of the possibility of ...Bd6. Now Black will need to develop with ...Be7.  7.Bf4  also develops our bishop and keeps everything together. It's the perfect move!   7.Nc3?!  was played by Cheparinov, but I don't see why you would allow Black to play  7...Bb4!  ∞  , so I don't like this approach. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Cheparinov,I @@StartBracket@@2686@@EndBracket@@-Marholev,D @@StartBracket@@2348@@EndBracket@@ Kozloduy 2014 }
7... Bb4+ 8. Kf2
{ A very interesting way of playing. This unusual move somehow speeds up White's development - the king protects the g2-pawn, which will allow us to develop our pieces faster. }
8... d5
{ This is a move that's always interesting against the Scotch, and White needs to be aware of it. }
9. exd5 Qf5
{ The only move to fight back, forking the bishop and the pawn on d5. Black tries to remove our dark-squared bishop so that it's harder for us to defend on the diagonal a7-g1. }
10. Qe2+ { This already looks suspicious for Black. } 10... Kf8
{ A weird move, but it's possible. } 11. dxc6 Qxf4 12. g3
{ A key move to give White's king the g2-square in case of any ...Ng4+ or ...Ne4+. The black queen has to make a decision of where to go, and next we'll try to develop with Bg2. }
12... Ng4+ { A possible move, but very risky! } 13. Kg2
{ Thank to g3 we have this important escape square! } 13... Ne3+
{ The only move for Black! Otherwise we win a piece. } 14. Kg1
{ The only way to play for the win! If  14.Kf2  Black will be happy to repeat with  14...Ng4+  . }
14... Qh6 { The queen needs to keep protecting the e3-knight. } 15. c3
{ It's huge that we have a knight on b3, as it fully controls the activity of Black's dark-squared bishop. }
15... Bd6 16. N1d2
{ Threatening Re1 to win the e3-the knight, for example  16...bxc6??  17.Re1+-  . We've also developed and coordinated our pieces more than Black has. }
16... Nxf1 17. Re1
{ A beautiful move that threatens mate on e8. We'll still take the knight on f1 next. }
