[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Qf6 5. Nb3
{ The best move in my opinion! White makes it impossible for Black to play ...Bc5, which would be a typical continuation for Black after 4...Qf6. Now Black has no decent square to develop the f8-bishop to. White also declines the knight trade, wich helps us keep our space advantage. If you have more space, it's usually better to avoid piece trades, and that's the case here. }
5... Qg6
{ A necessary move for Black to make sense of 4...Qf6 and to give the knight on g8 an important development square on f6. It's also a forcing move that pressures e4 and g2 at the same time. }
6. f3
{ The strongest way to defend e4. A move like  6.Nc3  would allow the annoying pin  6...Bb4  and we definitely don't want to allow Black to develop the f8-bishop actively. }
6... Nf6
{ This move is very logical because it develops and keeps multiple possibilities open for the bishop on f8. It also helps with possible ...d5 counterplay.Now White needs to continue in a way that doesn't allow Bb4. We need to pay special attention to this position because it was played by a strong GM, Jeffrey Xiong, in a relatively recent game. }
7. Bf4
{ A very flexible move! White is waiting for the f8-bishop to move and we get rid of the possibility of ...Bd6. Now Black will need to develop with ...Be7.  7.Bf4  also develops our bishop and keeps everything together. It's the perfect move!   7.Nc3?!  was played by Cheparinov, but I don't see why you would allow Black to play  7...Bb4!  ∞  , so I don't like this approach. 1-0 @@StartBracket@@29@@EndBracket@@ Cheparinov,I @@StartBracket@@2686@@EndBracket@@-Marholev,D @@StartBracket@@2348@@EndBracket@@ Kozloduy 2014 }
7... Bb4+ 8. Kf2
{ A very interesting way of playing. This unusual move somehow speeds up White's development - the king protects the g2-pawn, which will allow us to develop our pieces faster. }
8... O-O
{ 0-1 @@StartBracket@@41@@EndBracket@@ Shankland,S @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@-Xiong,J @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ Saint Louis 2019   8...a5!?  9.Bd3!  is similar to the mainline. White is attempting to play e5. }
9. Bd3
{ A more precise move than Sam's approach of  9.a3  . White leaves the black bishop on b4 for now and threatens e5, which would win a piece. }
9... Nh5
{ The only move to keep the fight fair. The alternative  9...Ne8  looks suspicious and very passive. }
10. Bxc7
{ An ugly looking move, but when you can win material and there is no clear way your opponent can punish you, you have to go for it. One of the advantages of the bishop being on b4 is that a move like  10...d6  would not only trap the c7-bishop but also the one on b4! That's an important detail in this crazy tactical position. }
10... a5
{ A key idea for Black. The reasoning behind this move is that after ...a4, the b3-knight will need to move, and then the c5-square will be available for the b4-bishop. }
11. g4
{ White wastes no time and goes for immediate counterplay. This is a very important tactical idea. Black is losing a piece so they will have to play extremely well to not get a completely lost position. }
