[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Other 4th Moves"]
[Black "4...g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This is not principled at all, but it's a logical development move and one that I have seen some GMs play. }
5. Nc3
{ Stopping any chance of a quick ...d5 by Black and trying to develop the queenside pieces in order to get a setup with long castling. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3 { White is ready to coordinate with Qd2 and O-O-O. } 6... Nf6
{ This is a tricky move because it attempts to play the annoying 7...Ng4. We don't have time to play  7.f3  since Black will play the freeing  7...d5!  Remember to always stop ...d5 for Black in the Scotch. }
7. Nxc6 bxc6
{ After  7...dxc6?!  8.Qxd8+  Kxd8  9.O-O-O+  ±  Black's doubled pawns and White's extra space give White a clear edge. }
8. e5 { This is the justification for playing 7.Nxc6. } 8... Ng8
{ This looks horrible for Black. } 9. f4
{ Locking down the g7-bishop is important. This move solidifies our space advantage. }
9... d5
{ This move doesn't force us to take en passant, so we leave Black's d-pawn alone. }
10. Qd2
{ White has good control over the c5 and d4-squares, so we should keep the pawn structure like this. For example, allowing Black to play ...c5 wouldn't be a good idea so we have moves like Na4 or Qf2 to keep Black from playing that. }
10... Ne7 11. O-O-O
{ There is nothing to worry about on the b-file, so White chooses to castle long. This speeds up our development and puts a rook on the d-file quickly. }
11... O-O 12. Bc5
{ White's space advantage is clear. Play might continue  12...f6!?  This move is necessary as sooner or later Black will need to open up the g7-bishop. It makes sense to do it now, as later it might not be possible anymore.  13.exf6  Bxf6  14.Ne4!  +-  You can see the value of having the rook on d1 and some of the power of long castling. }
