1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 g6
{ This is not principled at all, but it's a logical development move and one that I have seen some GMs play. }
5. Nc3
{ Stopping any chance of a quick ...d5 by Black and trying to develop the queenside pieces in order to get a setup with long castling. }
5... Bg7 6. Be3 { White is ready to coordinate with Qd2 and O-O-O. } 6... d6
{ Preparing 7...Nf6 so that White can't answer it with Nxc6 followed by e5. }
7. Qd2 Nf6 8. O-O-O
{ All of White's dreams have come true. We have finished developing the queenside, we didn't allow Black to play ...d5, and so we have good control over the center. }
