{ There are many moves here that give White an advantage, but I like the simplicity of this move. }
5... bxc6 6. exd5
{ The problem for Black is that they have to recapture with the queen. } 6...
Qxd5
{ The only move to keep the material balance.   Black has no good answer after  6...cxd5?  7.Bb5+!  +- }
7. Qe2+ Qe6
{ Any other move like  7...Be7  or  7...Be6  will be answered with  8.Nc3  , giving us a free tempo on Black's queen. }
8. Nc3 Nf6
{ If Black decides to take on e2 it will give us speedy development, so it would be wise for Black to avoid that. }
9. Bf4 { Targeting c7 and preparing to castle long. } 9... Bd6 10. Bg3
{ An important move! White doesn't want to take on d6 and undouble the pawns for Black. There is no reason to rush, so we let Black be the one to make the exchange. }
10... O-O 11. Qxe6
{ Let's keep it simple and not give Black a chance to avoid the queen trade. Scotch players need to be ok with winning endgames like this one, so get ready for that! }
11... Bxe6 12. O-O-O
{ And the endgame is very comfortable for White. Black's pawn structure is not in good shape and White's pieces are easier to activate. }
