[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Other 4th Moves"]
[Black "4...Nxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ This move is very popular online, but unheard of in top player's games. Black helps White to quickly centralize White's queen, which immediately leads to a very good position for White. }
5. Qxd4 Qf6
{ A necessity for Black, as leaving our queen unchallenged on d4 would be even more problematic. }
6. Qc4
{ Not the only way to get an advantage, but I like the part where we counter Black's setup with an attack on c7. }
6... c6
{ Stopping Nb5 or Nd5 after we've developed our knight to c3. This moves does leave a weakness on the d-file that White can use to create pressure, later on in the middlegame.   After  6...Qc6  7.Nc3!  ±  the endgame is very comfortable for White, though this is not the only way to get an advantage. Development is always good whenever possible so this makes sense. We let Black exchange on c4, in which case White will develop another piece.   6...Bd6  would be a weird move to play. I do not like it at all.  7.Nc3±  Threatening Nb5 and developing at the same time. White's play is simple: we finish our development and can then castle either way. }
7. Nc3 b5
{ Black continues bothering our queen, but with no actual improvement on minor piece development. }
8. Qd3 { We don't really have a choice here, but this move is simple enough. }
8... b4 9. Na4
{ The knight feels wrong on a4, but in reality it's totally fine. The goal is to bring it back via the c5-square in the future. }
9... Qe6 { Black tries to play ...d5 as usual. } 10. Be3
{ Developing and removing the pin on the e4-pawn. As you can see, White is developing the queenside first so they can quickly castle long. }
10... Nf6 11. f3
{ While developing we always prioritize protecting our hanging material, either by defending our pieces or by taking our opponent's ones whenever possible. }
11... d5 12. Nc5
{ The knight is back in the game and it's stronger than ever! } 12... Bxc5
{ Moving the queen would only make things worse for Black, as it would waste a tempo in the opening when Black has only developed one piece. }
13. Bxc5
{ Now the black king cannot castle short while we are ready to castle long. In exchange, Black is not even winning a pawn, as while Black grabs the one on e4 we will take the pawn on b4. }
