1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... f6
{ This is as bad as it gets strategically, Black gives up the huge diagonal a2-g8 which give us an easy next move! }
4. Bc4
{ Quickly controlling the diagonal so we stop Black from short castling in the future. }
4... d6 { Black want's to get the pin on g4 and attack the d4-pawn. } 5. h3
{ A prophylactic approach! It's important to understand that Black's position is actually very solid. We have no easy target, and in these cases, the best way to punish your opponent is to continue playing for development and keeping the strength of your space in the center. }
5... Nge7 6. O-O
{ Again nothing special, we need to be patient. We also need to keep an eye on possible tactics or blunders while we continue our natural piece improvement. }
6... Bd7 7. a4
{ Taking the space on the queen side as well as threatening a future a5 follow up. Also giving our Bishop the possible Ba2 escape. }
