{ The automatic response for Black!   4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Bd7  6.Nc3  Nf6  We analyzed deeply this position on the chapter with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  d6  5.Bb5  . Please refer to that variation by following the order mentioned above. }
5. Bxc6
{ Black is now forced to take with the Bishop on c6 because of the hanging pawn on e5. }
5... Bxc6 { 5...bxc6?  Losing a pawn right away.  6.dxe5  dxe5  7.Nxe5+- } 6.
Nc3
{ Now the e5 pawn is hanging again, so Black must protect it.   6.dxe5?  We cannot take yet because Black is targeting e4 with the Bishop.  6...dxe5⩱ }
6... f6
{ People love this move! It's, in fact, very solid and gives Black the possibility of g7-g5. So get ready to see something like this happening to you! Our approach is as usual to finish developing our minor pieces, castle and improve our rooks. }
7. Be3 Qe7
{ It seems like Black is targeting a lot, but are they? If they open the position it can only benefit White because we have more development and space. }
8. Qd3
{ The perfect position for the queen. This is the best way to coordinate rooks on this Philidor setup. White can only protect the e4-pawn but also have ideas like Qc4 or even Qa6 if a ...Nc6 ...bxc6 ever happen. }
8... g5 { I have seen this silly attacks too many times! } 9. a4
{ We see this move again! White increases the space on the queen side and now has moves like  9...--  10.Nb5!  and if Black plays  10...Bxb5  11.axb5  and open the file.   Finally, after @@StartFEN@@r3kbnr/ppp1q2p/2bp1p2/4p1p1/P2PP3/2NQBN2/1PP2PPP/R3K2R b KQkq a3 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9...h5  there's  10.Qc4+- }
