1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... d6
{ By far one of the most popular moves online for U1500 players. This is more like a bad version of the Philidor Defense than a Scotch setup, so we will treat it that way. We have plenty of ways to get an advantage here, but we also want to keep the position open so we can play a pawn structure that's more familiar. That's why I don't want to play the strong 4. d5, instead we are going with the other best move! }
4. Bb5
{ If you have seen the other similar lines @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  d6  5.Bb5  on this course, you won't be surprise by this move. We target the e5-pawn by pinning the Nc6. We also threatened to take on c6 and get double c-pawns. }
4... Bd7
{ The automatic response for Black!   4...exd4  5.Nxd4  Bd7  6.Nc3  Nf6  We analyzed deeply this position on the chapter with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/4p3/3PP3/5N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq d3 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3...exd4  4.Nxd4  d6  5.Bb5  . Please refer to that variation by following the order mentioned above. }
5. Bxc6
{ Black is now forced to take with the Bishop on c6 because of the hanging pawn on e5. }
5... Bxc6 { 5...bxc6?  Losing a pawn right away.  6.dxe5  dxe5  7.Nxe5+- } 6.
Nc3
{ Now the e5 pawn is hanging again, so Black must protect it.   6.dxe5?  We cannot take yet because Black is targeting e4 with the Bishop.  6...dxe5⩱ }
6... Nf6 { We still need to protect the e4-pawn! } 7. Qd3
{ One of my favorite games in the Philidor was played by Grischuck, and it was an eye-opening. I never thought to place my queen on d3. Black is again struggling to protect e5, and so Ivanov decided to remove the pressure. }
7... exd4
{ Black cannot handle the pressure on e5 and needs to trade.   7...Qe7  Protecting the e5-pawn and trying to castle long.  8-O-O±  Necessary because of the indirect attack on e4. We need the f1 rook to quickly access e1. Black cannot take on e4 because it will lose a lot of material. }
8. Nxd4 Be7
{ 8...Nd7?!  9.Qg3!  A more aggressive approach that helps White's queen become more active by targeting the g7-pawn. We also have Bg5 ideas as a follow-up, speeding up the development of our pieces.   9.Nxc6?!  A little early and not the best, but the game is still an amazing model to follow to increase your possibilities/ideas on this position. 1-0 Grischuk-Ivanov, Dagomys 2010.  9...Qf6  A simple move like this is already problematic after the strong attacking move:  10.Ndb5!± }
9. f3 { Stopping ...Ng4 and preparing for Be3 and O-O-O. } 9... O-O
{ Black continues developing and gets ready to break on d5. In this position, the way we will deal with a d5 is by taking c6 and doubling the c-pawns, in which case our pawn structure will be greatly improved! }
10. Be3 { We don't really mind d5! } 10... d5 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O-O
{ We are now targeting the pawn on d5 and after trades with  12...dxe4  13.Nxe4  Black creates the doubled isolated c-pawns, giving White an easy endgame. }
