1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... f5
{ This line does require some precise tactics, but it's also really bad for Black. }
4. Nxe5 { We simply take the pawn and open up the strong Qh5 check! } 4... fxe4
5. Nc3
{ The more aggressive approach! We target e4 and still keep our strong Qh5 alive! }
5... Nxe5
{ 5...Nf6  Not solid enough!  6.Bc4!  d5  Looks like Black is escaping, but it's not the case!  7.Nxd5+- }
6. dxe5 { Now this pawn gives us the important en passant vs a ...d5 defense. }
6... Bb4
{ Indirectly protecting the e4-pawn and developing is Black's best hope } 7.
Qd4 Bxc3+ { The only way to keep the e4-pawn alive. } 8. Qxc3 Ne7 9. Bc4
{ White is practically winning, the Black king doesn't have an easy way to castle and White will continue with moves like O-O and target the weak e4-pawn. If Black plays d5, we can go ahead. }
