1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... d5 4. Nxe5 { By far the best move! } 4... Nxe5
{ This only makes things easier for White. Now Black will have to suffer in a very inferior endgame. }
5. dxe5 dxe4 { Getting the pawn back but paying the prize for not castling. }
6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nc3
{ Now White targets the e4-pawn first, and so the initiative is very clear. }
7... Bb4 { Developing and defending at the same time by using the pin. } 8. Bd2
{ It's much harder for Black to attack the e5-pawn than it's for White to attack the e4 one. }
8... Bxc3 9. Bxc3
{ Whit has the bishop pair and a weak pawn on e4 to target. After O-O-O, Bc4 and Rhe1, Black is in big trouble. }
