1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... d5 4. Nxe5 { By far the best move! } 4... dxe4 5. Bb5
{ We're going to see this pin used plenty of times on these dubious lines because it's a quick way of getting the initiative by developing and attacking at the same time. }
5... Bd7 6. Bxc6
{ Another typical approach, we don't mind giving up the light square bishop because Blacks's light square bishop is doing very little. Instead, we want to keep our strong knight on e5! }
6... Bxc6
{ 6...bxc6  7.O-O±  Now we just put all of our forces into attacking e4. } 7.
O-O
{ We can take on c6 whenever we want, so we keep our monster knight a little longer. Now we are ready to target e4. }
7... Bd6
{ After this move, Black can no longer play the Bb4 pin so we can go on and play Nc3. But before we do that, we need to stop Bxe5. }
8. Nxc6 { It's finally time to give up our knight for the c6 bishop! } 8...
bxc6 9. Nc3
{ And the position is falling apart for Black. Not only White is ahead of development, but Black has multiple weak pawns. An easy example of how we can break Black's pawn structure is  9...f5  10.f3!±  with plenty of potential! }
