1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... Bd6 4. dxe5
{ I like this move because it proves quickly why this is such a bad opening decision for Black. Black will have to waste tempi and White will only increase their space in the center.   4.c3±  is also a pretty logical move! White simply keeps the space, and now Black has to figure out what to do with the Bc8. }
4... Nxe5 5. Nxe5 Bxe5 6. f4 Bf6 { All forcing so far! } 7. Bd3 d6 8. O-O
{ Again, we based our advantage on easy development and control of the center! }
8... Ne7 9. Nc3
{ There are no clear targets or weaknesses, so we keep coordinating our pieces! }
9... O-O 10. Bd2
{ With a big initiative that's purely based on space and better piece mobility. White's next moves could be Qf3-Rhe1-Kh1 then at some point the strong e5! or even Nd5. }
