1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... Nf6 4. d5
{ Forces the Black knight to retreat right away and taking control of the initiative quickly.   4.dxe5±  A more open position approach that's also very strong. }
4... Ne7 5. Nxe5 Nxe4 { Black has to take the pawn!   5...d6?  6.Bb5++- } 6.
Qe2
{ Quickly putting pressure on the e-file and setting up a pin with discovered attack possibilities. }
6... Nd6
{ Black is basically in Zugzwang and unable to do much. The only way to coordinate is to go with ...g6-...Bg7-...O-O which is why White's next move is so important.   6...f5  7.Nd2!±  Trying to remove the knight from e4 so that we can target the knight that's pinned on e7. }
7. h4
{ Another time where we go for the h4 move! The idea is to go h5 or maybe Rh3. }
7... f6 { 7...g6  8.h5+-  With a crushing attack. } 8. Nf3 Kf7
{ Another wait to coordinate, but not a very good-looking one. } 9. Nc3
{ White is now ready to castle long and start a powerful attack on the kingside. }
