1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
{ All the lines included in this chapter are mostly played online, but you would be surprise how often you will encounter them. I, personally, have seen too many of my student's games that I felt the need of dedicating the time to give you guys ideas on how to approach them. They are not good moves for Black, I can assure you, but it's always good to be prepared! }
3... Nf6 4. d5
{ Forces the Black knight to retreat right away and taking control of the initiative quickly.   4.dxe5±  A more open position approach that's also very strong. }
4... Nb8 5. Nxe5 { We want to open the position when we can! } 5... Qe7
{ 5...Nxe4?  Too dangerous!  6.Qe2!  Qe7  The best move!  7.Qxe4  d6  8.f4±  And White will either keep the pawn or Black will have a very ugly looking position. }
6. Nd3 { Centralizing the knight a little more! } 6... Qxe4+
{ A good try! Black tries to make a point of gaining material in exchange for the delay of development.   6...Nxe4  7.Be2±  And White has a pretty large advantage in development. Black has to figure out what to do with the Qe7 so they can short castle. White's plan is to O-O and play Re1 or if you like to long castle you can go Be3-Nd2 and O-O-O as soon as possible. Either way, White will have a big edge on space and initiative. }
7. Be2 Qxg2 { Taking this pawn will only increase White's initiative! } 8. Bf3
Qh3 9. Qe2+
{ Since we are castling long, the pawn doesn't really matter, the opposite castle position will only benefit White because the g-file is open. }
9... Be7 10. d6
{ It's all about the d5-square for our knights. We also make the c8-bishop pretty bad! }
10... cxd6 11. Nc3 O-O { Finally, Black castles, but it's already too late! }
12. Nf4 { The bomb move!  12.Qxe7??  Re8-+ } 12... Qh4 13. Nfd5
{ And now you can see why we sacrifice the pawn on d6. We are down two pawns, but we don't need to rush , we can continue giving our king some more safety with moves like Be3 then followed by O-O-O and at that point, we can start taking material back. That's, of course, if Black doesn't blunder right away. }
13... Nc6
{ Protecting the bishop on e7 and developing. Also, giving the Ra8 the possibility of going to b8. }
14. Be3 { Followed by O-O-O and Rhg1, with an advantage. } *

